export const EXPLANATIONS = {
"A-001-001-001": "In an RL circuit the time constant τ = L/R is the time for the current to rise to 63.2% of its final value — one time constant. The key word is current: an inductor opposes a sudden change in current, so it builds up gradually, which rules out the distractors that talk about voltage. 36.8% is the leftover fraction in a decay (the complement of 63.2%), not the rising value.",
"A-001-001-002": "Reaching 63.2% of the final value always takes exactly one time constant; for an RC circuit τ = R × C. The figure 63.2% is 1 − 1/e, the defining one-time-constant level. The other phrases ('exponential rate', 'time factor', 'exponential period') are not the accepted term.",
"A-001-001-003": "One time constant is the time for the current to reach 63.2% of its final value; for an RL circuit τ = L/R. 63.2% (which is 1 − 1/e) is the standard one-time-constant point. The alternative phrasings are not recognized terminology.",
"A-001-001-004": "Discharging to 36.8% of the starting charge takes one time constant, because after one τ a decaying quantity falls to 1/e ≈ 36.8% of its initial value. Charging rises to 63.2% while discharging falls to 36.8% — the two are complements. The other phrases are not the recognized term.",
"A-001-001-005": "Back EMF is a voltage that opposes the applied EMF (Lenz's law). When the current through an inductor changes, the inductor induces a voltage that fights that change; it is a voltage, not a current, which eliminates the current-based options. This opposition is exactly why current in an inductor builds up gradually rather than instantly.",
"A-001-001-006": "After n time constants a charging capacitor reaches (1 − e⁻ⁿ) of the supply voltage. For n = 2: 1 − e⁻² = 1 − 0.135 = 0.865, i.e. 86.5%. 63.2% is the level after just one time constant and 36.8% is the fraction still remaining, so both are traps.",
"A-001-001-007": "A discharging capacitor falls to e⁻ⁿ of its starting voltage after n time constants. For n = 2: e⁻² = 0.135, i.e. 13.5% remaining. 36.8% applies after only one time constant, and 86.5% is the charging (complement) value, so neither fits two time constants of discharge.",
"A-001-001-008": "The time constant is τ = R × C. Convert first: 470 kΩ = 470 000 Ω and 100 µF = 100×10⁻⁶ F, so τ = 470 000 × 100×10⁻⁶ = 47 seconds. The wrong answers come from slipping the decimal point, so always convert kΩ and µF to ohms and farads before multiplying.",
"A-001-001-009": "Time constant τ = R × C = 470 000 Ω × 470×10⁻⁶ F = 220.9 ≈ 221 seconds. Convert 470 kΩ → 470 000 Ω and 470 µF → 470×10⁻⁶ F before multiplying. The much larger answers come from leaving the values in kΩ or µF.",
"A-001-001-010": "Time constant τ = R × C = 470 000 Ω × 220×10⁻⁶ F = 103.4 ≈ 103 seconds. Remember to convert 470 kΩ → 470 000 Ω and 220 µF → 220×10⁻⁶ F. Mishandling those powers of ten produces the distractor values.",
"A-001-002-001": "Skin effect means that as frequency increases, RF current crowds into a thinner layer near the conductor's surface. It increases with frequency (not decreases, as one distractor claims) and is caused by induced eddy currents and self-inductance, not by heating. The thinner the effective conducting layer, the higher the conductor's RF resistance.",
"A-001-002-002": "Skin effect is the phenomenon that forces RF current to flow mostly along the conductor's surface. The piezoelectric effect concerns mechanical stress in crystals, and resonance concerns reactive circuits, so neither applies. 'Layer effect' is not a real term.",
"A-001-002-003": "Because of skin effect, almost all RF current flows along the surface of the conductor, not through its centre. Magnetic fields exist around a current-carrying wire, but the current itself travels in a thin surface layer at radio frequencies. This is why hollow tubing or silver plating works as well as solid wire for RF.",
"A-001-002-004": "This surface crowding is skin effect, driven by self-inductance that increasingly impedes current toward the conductor's centre as frequency rises. The DC resistance is actually lower than the RF resistance (the opposite of one distractor), because at DC the whole cross-section carries current. Interior heating is a consequence in some cases, not the cause.",
"A-001-002-005": "Skin effect makes a conductor's RF resistance higher than its DC resistance, because RF current uses only a thin surface layer instead of the full cross-section. With less effective copper carrying the current, resistance rises with frequency. The 'Hertzberg effect' and conductor non-linearity are not the cause, and insulation does not carry the current.",
"A-001-002-006": "The farad (F) is the unit of capacitance — how much charge a capacitor stores per volt (C = Q/V). The coulomb measures charge itself, the volt measures potential, and the watt measures power, so none of those describe storage capacity. One farad equals one coulomb per volt.",
"A-001-002-007": "A wire carrying a current is surrounded by a magnetic field (the magnetic part of the electromagnetic field) that circles the conductor. An electrostatic field arises from static charge or a voltage difference, not from current flow, so that option is wrong. The field strengthens with more current and weakens with distance.",
"A-001-002-008": "The magnetic field circles the conductor, and its direction relative to electron flow is given by the left-hand rule: point the thumb along the electron flow and the curled fingers show the field direction. (Using conventional current, which flows opposite to electrons, you would use the right-hand rule instead.) The field is not in the same direction as the current and not in all directions, so those options are wrong.",
"A-001-002-009": "Energy stored in an electric or magnetic field is potential energy — energy held by virtue of configuration and ready to do work. Kinetic energy is the energy of motion, which does not describe a static stored field. 'Ampere-joules' and 'joule-coulombs' are not real units of energy.",
"A-001-002-010": "Between a capacitor's charged plates is an electrostatic (electric) field, created by the voltage difference across them. No steady current flows through an ideal dielectric, and stored charge does not create a magnetic field, so those options are wrong. This electric field is where the capacitor's energy is stored.",
"A-001-002-011": "Energy stored in an inductor is W = ½LI², so besides current it depends on the inductance L, whose unit is the henry. The farad is for capacitance and the coulomb for charge, so they don't apply to an inductor. The watt is a unit of power, not the property that sets stored energy.",
"A-001-003-001": "Resonant frequency is f = 1 / (2π√(LC)), identical for series and parallel RLC. With L = 50 µH = 50×10⁻⁶ H and C = 40 pF = 40×10⁻¹² F, LC = 2×10⁻¹⁵ and √(LC) ≈ 4.47×10⁻⁸, so f ≈ 1/(2π × 4.47×10⁻⁸) ≈ 3.56 MHz. R does not appear in the formula, and the kHz options are unit-scale traps.",
"A-001-003-002": "Use f = 1 / (2π√(LC)). With L = 40×10⁻⁶ H and C = 200×10⁻¹² F, LC = 8×10⁻¹⁵ and √(LC) ≈ 8.94×10⁻⁸, so f ≈ 1.78 MHz. Keeping the 10⁻⁶ and 10⁻¹² factors straight is what lands the answer in MHz rather than the kHz traps.",
"A-001-003-003": "Use f = 1 / (2π√(LC)). With L = 50×10⁻⁶ H and C = 10×10⁻¹² F, LC = 5×10⁻¹⁶ and √(LC) ≈ 2.24×10⁻⁸, giving f ≈ 7.12 MHz. Resistance is not in the formula, so it has no effect on resonance.",
"A-001-003-004": "Use f = 1 / (2π√(LC)). With L = 25×10⁻⁶ H and C = 10×10⁻¹² F, LC = 2.5×10⁻¹⁶ and √(LC) ≈ 1.58×10⁻⁸, so f ≈ 10.1 MHz. The kHz answers are off by a factor of 1000 — a unit trap.",
"A-001-003-005": "Use f = 1 / (2π√(LC)). With L = 3×10⁻⁶ H and C = 40×10⁻¹² F, LC = 1.2×10⁻¹⁶ and √(LC) ≈ 1.10×10⁻⁸, giving f ≈ 14.5 MHz. Only L and C set resonance, so the resistor value is irrelevant.",
"A-001-003-006": "Use f = 1 / (2π√(LC)). With L = 4×10⁻⁶ H and C = 20×10⁻¹² F, LC = 8×10⁻¹⁷ and √(LC) ≈ 8.94×10⁻⁹, so f ≈ 17.8 MHz. Track the powers of ten carefully to avoid the kHz distractors.",
"A-001-003-007": "Use f = 1 / (2π√(LC)). With L = 8×10⁻⁶ H and C = 7×10⁻¹² F, LC = 5.6×10⁻¹⁷ and √(LC) ≈ 7.48×10⁻⁹, giving f ≈ 21.3 MHz. The answer is in MHz once the µH and pF factors are handled correctly.",
"A-001-003-008": "Use f = 1 / (2π√(LC)). With L = 3×10⁻⁶ H and C = 15×10⁻¹² F, LC = 4.5×10⁻¹⁷ and √(LC) ≈ 6.71×10⁻⁹, so f ≈ 23.7 MHz. Resistance does not enter the resonance formula.",
"A-001-003-009": "Use f = 1 / (2π√(LC)). With L = 4×10⁻⁶ H and C = 8×10⁻¹² F, LC = 3.2×10⁻¹⁷ and √(LC) ≈ 5.66×10⁻⁹, giving f ≈ 28.1 MHz. Keep the 10⁻⁶ and 10⁻¹² straight to stay in MHz.",
"A-001-003-010": "Use f = 1 / (2π√(LC)). With L = 1×10⁻⁶ H and C = 9×10⁻¹² F, LC = 9×10⁻¹⁸ and √(LC) = 3×10⁻⁹, so f ≈ 1/(2π × 3×10⁻⁹) ≈ 53.1 MHz. The small L and C push resonance high into VHF.",
"A-001-003-011": "Rearrange f = 1/(2π√(LC)) to C = 1 / ((2πf)² × L). With f = 14.25×10⁶ Hz, 2πf ≈ 8.95×10⁷ and (2πf)² ≈ 8.0×10¹⁵; dividing by L = 2.84×10⁻⁶ H gives C ≈ 44×10⁻¹² F = 44 pF. The microfarad options are off by 10⁶, a unit trap.",
"A-001-004-001": "For a parallel RLC circuit the resonant frequency is still f = 1 / (2π√(LC)); R does not affect it. With L = 1×10⁻⁶ H and C = 10×10⁻¹² F, LC = 1×10⁻¹⁷ and √(LC) ≈ 3.16×10⁻⁹, so f ≈ 50.3 MHz. The 4.7 kΩ is a red herring for the resonance calculation.",
"A-001-004-002": "Resonance is f = 1 / (2π√(LC)) (R has no effect). With L = 2×10⁻⁶ H and C = 15×10⁻¹² F, LC = 3×10⁻¹⁷ and √(LC) ≈ 5.48×10⁻⁹, so f ≈ 29.1 MHz. The kHz answers are a factor-of-1000 trap.",
"A-001-004-003": "Resonance is f = 1 / (2π√(LC)); the resistor doesn't change it. With L = 5×10⁻⁶ H and C = 9×10⁻¹² F, LC = 4.5×10⁻¹⁷ and √(LC) ≈ 6.71×10⁻⁹, giving f ≈ 23.7 MHz. Only L and C determine resonant frequency.",
"A-001-004-004": "Resonance is f = 1 / (2π√(LC)). With L = 2×10⁻⁶ H and C = 30×10⁻¹² F, LC = 6×10⁻¹⁷ and √(LC) ≈ 7.75×10⁻⁹, so f ≈ 20.5 MHz. R is irrelevant to the resonant frequency.",
"A-001-004-005": "Resonance is f = 1 / (2π√(LC)). With L = 15×10⁻⁶ H and C = 5×10⁻¹² F, LC = 7.5×10⁻¹⁷ and √(LC) ≈ 8.66×10⁻⁹, giving f ≈ 18.4 MHz. Watch the kHz distractors created by mishandling µH and pF.",
"A-001-004-006": "Resonance is f = 1 / (2π√(LC)). With L = 3×10⁻⁶ H and C = 40×10⁻¹² F, LC = 1.2×10⁻¹⁶ and √(LC) ≈ 1.10×10⁻⁸, so f ≈ 14.5 MHz. The resistor does not enter the formula.",
"A-001-004-007": "Resonance is f = 1 / (2π√(LC)). With L = 40×10⁻⁶ H and C = 6×10⁻¹² F, LC = 2.4×10⁻¹⁶ and √(LC) ≈ 1.55×10⁻⁸, so f ≈ 10.3 MHz. Only L and C set the resonant frequency.",
"A-001-004-008": "Resonance is f = 1 / (2π√(LC)). With L = 10×10⁻⁶ H and C = 50×10⁻¹² F, LC = 5×10⁻¹⁶ and √(LC) ≈ 2.24×10⁻⁸, giving f ≈ 7.12 MHz. The kHz options are off by a factor of 1000.",
"A-001-004-009": "Resonance is f = 1 / (2π√(LC)). With L = 200×10⁻⁶ H and C = 10×10⁻¹² F, LC = 2×10⁻¹⁵ and √(LC) ≈ 4.47×10⁻⁸, so f ≈ 3.56 MHz. The large inductance pulls the resonant frequency down to the 80 m region.",
"A-001-004-010": "Resonance is f = 1 / (2π√(LC)). With L = 90×10⁻⁶ H and C = 100×10⁻¹² F, LC = 9×10⁻¹⁵ and √(LC) ≈ 9.49×10⁻⁸, giving f ≈ 1.68 MHz. Keep the µH and pF powers of ten straight to avoid the kHz traps.",
"A-001-004-011": "Rearrange f = 1/(2π√(LC)) to L = 1 / ((2πf)² × C). With f = 14.25×10⁶ Hz, (2πf)² ≈ 8.0×10¹⁵; dividing by C = 44×10⁻¹² F gives L ≈ 2.8×10⁻⁶ H = 2.8 µH. The millihenry options are off by a factor of 1000 or more — unit traps.",
"A-001-005-001": "For a parallel resonant circuit, Q = R / (2πfL) = R / X_L. Here X_L = 2π × 14.128×10⁶ × 2.7×10⁻⁶ ≈ 240 Ω, so Q = 18 000 / 240 ≈ 75.1. This is the parallel form, where Q rises with R; the series form Q = X_L/R would give a wrong, tiny value.",
"A-001-005-002": "Parallel Q = R / (2πfL). X_L = 2π × 14.128×10⁶ × 4.7×10⁻⁶ ≈ 417 Ω, so Q = 18 000 / 417 ≈ 43.1. A larger inductance means a larger X_L and thus a lower Q for the same R.",
"A-001-005-003": "Parallel Q = R / (2πfL). X_L = 2π × 4.468×10⁶ × 47×10⁻⁶ ≈ 1320 Ω, so Q = 180 / 1320 ≈ 0.136. A small R with a large X_L gives a very low Q; the answers above 1 come from inverting the ratio.",
"A-001-005-004": "Parallel Q = R / (2πfL). X_L = 2π × 14.225×10⁶ × 3.5×10⁻⁶ ≈ 313 Ω, so Q = 10 000 / 313 ≈ 31.9. Use the parallel form (R divided by X_L), not the series form.",
"A-001-005-005": "Parallel Q = R / (2πfL). X_L = 2π × 7.125×10⁶ × 8.2×10⁻⁶ ≈ 367 Ω, so Q = 1000 / 367 ≈ 2.73. Here R is only a few times X_L, so the Q is modest.",
"A-001-005-006": "Parallel Q = R / (2πfL). X_L = 2π × 7.125×10⁶ × 10.1×10⁻⁶ ≈ 452 Ω, so Q = 100 / 452 ≈ 0.221. Because R is smaller than X_L, the Q is below 1.",
"A-001-005-007": "Parallel Q = R / (2πfL). X_L = 2π × 7.125×10⁶ × 12.6×10⁻⁶ ≈ 564 Ω, so Q = 22 000 / 564 ≈ 39. The large R relative to X_L gives a high Q.",
"A-001-005-008": "Parallel Q = R / (2πfL). X_L = 2π × 3.625×10⁶ × 3×10⁻⁶ ≈ 68.3 Ω, so Q = 2200 / 68.3 ≈ 32.2. A small inductive reactance with a large R yields a high Q.",
"A-001-005-009": "Parallel Q = R / (2πfL). X_L = 2π × 3.625×10⁶ × 42×10⁻⁶ ≈ 957 Ω, so Q = 220 / 957 ≈ 0.23. A small R against a large X_L gives a Q well below 1.",
"A-001-005-010": "Parallel Q = R / (2πfL). X_L = 2π × 3.625×10⁶ × 43×10⁻⁶ ≈ 979 Ω, so Q = 1800 / 979 ≈ 1.84. Remember to divide R by X_L for a parallel circuit.",
"A-001-005-011": "Bandwidth = f / Q, so lowering Q widens the bandwidth. Adding a resistor (a deliberate loss/load) to a parallel resonant circuit lowers its Q and therefore broadens its response. A resistor cannot raise Q, and it does not change the resonant frequency (set by L and C), which eliminates the other options.",
"A-002-001-001": "Silicon and germanium are the classic semiconductor elements: their conductivity sits between that of metals and insulators, showing both metallic and non-metallic behaviour. The distractors include galena (lead sulphide, an old crystal-detector mineral, not a base element here) and gold, which is a pure conductor, so neither pair fits the description of two semiconductor elements.",
"A-002-001-002": "Gallium-arsenide (GaAs) lets electrons move faster than in silicon or germanium, so it can amplify and switch at very high speeds, which is exactly what microwave frequencies demand. That speed advantage is wasted at very low frequencies and GaAs is not chosen for high-power or ordinary bipolar-transistor roles, so microwave use is the answer.",
"A-002-001-003": "Doping pure silicon or germanium with an element that has fewer outer electrons creates 'holes,' leaving fewer free electrons than the pure crystal; this is P-type material (P for positive holes). N-type is the opposite, having extra free electrons, so it is the tempting wrong choice.",
"A-002-001-004": "Doping the crystal with an element that has extra outer electrons adds free electrons beyond what the pure crystal has, giving N-type material (N for negative carriers). P-type is the reverse, with fewer electrons and more holes, so it is the natural distractor.",
"A-002-001-005": "In P-type material the dopant creates an excess of holes, so holes are the majority carriers and electrons are the minority. Free electrons are the majority carriers in N-type, not P-type, which is why that distractor is tempting; protons and neutrons stay locked in the nucleus and never carry current.",
"A-002-001-006": "N-type material is doped to have extra free electrons, so free electrons are its majority carriers. Holes are the majority carriers in P-type material, making that the tempting wrong answer; protons and neutrons are bound in the nucleus and do not move as charge carriers.",
"A-002-001-007": "In its pure (undoped) state silicon has almost no free charge carriers, so it conducts very poorly and behaves as a good insulator; the exam treats pure silicon as an insulator for this reason. Only after doping with impurities does it act as a useful semiconductor, so 'a semiconductor' is the tempting answer but here the key wants its pure-state behaviour, an insulator.",
"A-002-001-008": "A semiconductor is named for exactly this behaviour: it conducts under some conditions and blocks current under others, sitting between an insulator and a conductor. N-type and P-type describe doped semiconductors specifically, and 'intrinsic' just means undoped, so 'semiconductor' is the general term being asked for.",
"A-002-001-009": "Silicon is the standard material for making semiconductors because its four outer electrons form a crystal that can be doped to control conductivity. Copper is a conductor and sulphur is essentially an insulator, while tantalum is used in capacitors, so none of those make semiconductors.",
"A-002-001-010": "In their pure state semiconductors like silicon have very few free charge carriers, so they conduct poorly and behave as good insulators. Only after doping with impurities do they become useful as semiconductor devices; tuned circuits and inductors are unrelated component types.",
"A-002-001-011": "Doping means deliberately adding tiny amounts of impurity atoms to pure silicon or germanium to create extra electrons (N-type) or holes (P-type). Adding loose protons, ions, or electrons is not how doping works; it is the impurity atoms built into the crystal lattice that change its conductivity.",
"A-002-002-001": "A Zener diode, operated in reverse breakdown, holds a nearly constant voltage across itself even as the current through it changes, which is why it is used as a voltage reference or regulator. The distractor about variable capacitance describes a varactor, not a Zener.",
"A-002-002-002": "A varactor diode is designed so its reverse-biased junction acts like a capacitor whose value changes with the applied voltage, useful for voltage-tuned circuits and AFC. A Zener holds a constant voltage, so it is the tempting but wrong choice here.",
"A-002-002-003": "The hot-carrier or Schottky diode switches very fast and has a low forward voltage, making it ideal as a VHF and UHF mixer and detector. A varactor would be used for variable capacitance and a Zener for a voltage reference, so those distractors describe other diode types.",
"A-002-002-004": "Forward current heats the junction, and too much heat destroys the diode, so junction temperature sets the maximum forward current rating. Peak inverse voltage is a separate rating that limits reverse voltage, not forward current, so it is a tempting but incorrect choice.",
"A-002-002-005": "Junction diodes are rated for the two stresses that can destroy them: maximum forward current (which heats the junction) and peak inverse voltage or PIV (the reverse voltage before breakdown). Reverse current and capacitance are not the defining ratings, so answers built around them are wrong.",
"A-002-002-006": "Structurally, semiconductor diodes are either junction types (a P-N boundary inside the crystal) or point-contact types (a fine wire touching the semiconductor). Vacuum and electrolytic refer to tube and capacitor technology, not semiconductor diode construction.",
"A-002-002-007": "A point-contact diode has very low capacitance because of its tiny contact area, so it works well as an RF detector at high frequencies. Its small junction cannot handle high voltage or steady current, ruling out the rectifier and constant-source distractors.",
"A-002-002-008": "A PIN diode acts like a current-controlled resistor at RF, so with a DC bias it makes an excellent RF switch or attenuator. It is not used as a high-voltage rectifier or as constant current/voltage source, which are roles for other devices.",
"A-002-002-009": "A Zener diode in reverse breakdown holds a steady voltage, so it is used to regulate (stabilize) voltage. It does not dissipate, decrease, or increase voltage or current as a primary purpose; maintaining a constant reference voltage is its job.",
"A-002-002-010": "Power is P = V × I, so the current is I = P / V. With P = 50 W and V = 10 V, I = 50 / 10 = 5 amperes. The decimal-point distractors (0.5 and 0.05) come from misplacing the division, so always divide watts by volts to get amperes.",
"A-002-002-011": "A Zener's power rating is given at 25 °C; raising the temperature leaves less safe margin for heat dissipation, so the power-handling capability becomes less. Components must be derated as they get hotter, so 'greater' or 'the same' is incorrect.",
"A-002-003-001": "Alpha (α) is the ratio of collector current to emitter current, slightly less than 1 because a tiny part of the emitter current leaves through the base. The change relative to base current defines beta, not alpha, so that is the tempting wrong answer.",
"A-002-003-002": "Beta (β) is the current gain measured as the change in collector current divided by the change in base current, typically tens to hundreds. The collector-to-emitter ratio defines alpha, so that distractor confuses the two key transistor parameters.",
"A-002-003-003": "An NPN transistor conducts electrons from a negative emitter to a positive collector when its base is made positive relative to the emitter, the standard NPN bias. A PNP works with reversed polarities, so it is the tempting opposite answer.",
"A-002-003-004": "Alpha is specified in common-base configuration, where it represents the forward current gain (collector current change versus emitter current change). It is a current relationship, not a voltage one, so the voltage-gain distractors are wrong.",
"A-002-003-005": "The change in collector current with respect to base current is the definition of beta, the common-emitter current gain. Alpha is the collector-to-emitter ratio instead, so it is the natural distractor to watch for.",
"A-002-003-006": "Alpha is defined for the common-base configuration, where the input is the emitter current and the output is the collector current. Common-emitter is where beta is defined, so it is the tempting wrong choice.",
"A-002-003-007": "Beta, the current gain, is specified for the common-emitter or common-collector configurations, since both use base current as the input reference. Common-base is the configuration for alpha, so answers including it are incorrect.",
"A-002-003-008": "A PNP transistor conducts when its base is made negative, with current flowing from a positive emitter to a negative collector, the mirror image of NPN operation. An NPN works with the opposite polarities (positive base, negative emitter), so it is the tempting wrong answer.",
"A-002-003-009": "Alpha and beta are related by α = β / (1 + β); since beta is large, alpha works out just under 1. The other formulas misplace the plus or minus and the multiplication, so memorize this exact arrangement.",
"A-002-003-010": "Common-emitter and common-collector configurations use base current as input and give high to very high current gain (beta, often 50 to several hundred). Common-base gives a current gain of only about 1 (alpha), so its gain is far lower, making the 'about double' or 'about half' answers wrong.",
"A-002-003-011": "Beta is found from alpha by β = α / (1 - α); since alpha is just under 1, the small denominator makes beta large. The distractors swap the sign or use multiplication, so this is the formula to remember as the inverse of α = β/(1+β).",
"A-002-004-001": "An enhancement-mode FET has no conducting channel at zero gate voltage, so no current flows until gate voltage is applied to create (enhance) a channel. This is the opposite of a depletion-mode FET, which conducts with zero gate voltage, so watch the wording carefully.",
"A-002-004-002": "A depletion-mode FET is built with a channel already present, so current flows even with zero gate voltage; the gate voltage then depletes the channel to reduce current. An enhancement-mode FET is the opposite, having no channel until voltage is applied, so it is the tempting wrong answer.",
"A-002-004-003": "A MOSFET's gate insulation is extremely thin and easily punctured by static charges or voltage spikes, so a built-in Zener diode clamps excessive gate voltage to protect that insulation. The diode is for protection, not biasing or substrate protection, so those distractors miss its purpose.",
"A-002-004-004": "FET and CMOS devices have very thin gate insulation that static electricity can puncture, so they must be handled with anti-static precautions. They are not unusually light-sensitive or mechanically fragile, so static charge is the real hazard.",
"A-002-004-005": "An FET controls current with a voltage on an insulated or reverse-biased gate, drawing almost no gate current, so its input impedance is high; a bipolar transistor needs base current, giving it low input impedance. This high-impedance input is a key reason FETs are chosen for sensitive front ends.",
"A-002-004-006": "A JFET has three terminals: gate, drain, and source, analogous to the base, collector, and emitter of a bipolar transistor. Emitter/base/collector belong to bipolar transistors, so that pairing is the distractor to avoid.",
"A-002-004-007": "JFETs come in two basic polarities: N-channel and P-channel, depending on whether the conducting channel carries electrons or holes. High/low power and silicon/germanium are not the defining categories of JFET type.",
"A-002-004-008": "In an N-channel depletion MOSFET, conduction is by electrons moving through the already-present N channel, so it is simply n-channel depletion. The mismatched polarity and enhancement options describe other device types, so match the carrier (electrons → n-channel) and mode (depletion).",
"A-002-004-009": "In an N-channel enhancement MOSFET, gate voltage creates an N channel and electrons then conduct, so it is n-channel enhancement. There is no real 'q-channel,' and the p-channel options use the wrong carrier polarity for electron conduction.",
"A-002-004-010": "In a P-channel depletion MOSFET, conduction is by holes moving through the existing P channel, so it is p-channel depletion. Holes are positive carriers tied to P-type material, so the N-channel and nonexistent 'q-channel' options do not fit hole conduction.",
"A-002-004-011": "In a P-channel enhancement MOSFET, gate voltage forms a P channel and holes then conduct, so it is p-channel enhancement. Hole conduction always goes with P-type material, ruling out the N-channel and 'q-channel' distractors.",
"A-002-005-001": "An SCR has three terminals: anode, cathode, and gate, where a small gate pulse switches on the main anode-to-cathode current. Base/collector/emitter belong to transistors and gate/source/sink is not a real set, so anode/cathode/gate is the SCR's signature.",
"A-002-005-002": "An SCR is a switch with two stable states: fully conducting (latched on) and non-conducting (off). It does not oscillate or split into NPN/PNP conduction modes as its stable states, so 'conducting and non-conducting' is correct.",
"A-002-005-003": "Once triggered, an SCR conducts from anode to cathode just like an ordinary forward-biased junction (silicon rectifier) diode, with a low voltage drop. It does not behave like a Schottky, PIN, or varactor diode, which have different specialized characteristics.",
"A-002-005-004": "When gated 'on,' an SCR latches into conduction and drops only a small forward voltage, behaving like a forward-biased silicon rectifier. When gated 'off' it blocks current, so the 'off' option is the opposite of what is asked.",
"A-002-005-005": "An SCR is a four-layer PNPN device, which gives it its latching behaviour once triggered. The other layer orderings (NPPN, PNNP, PPNN) do not describe the standard SCR structure.",
"A-002-005-006": "The control terminal of an SCR is the gate; a small current into the gate triggers the device into conduction. The anode and cathode carry the main current and 'emitter' belongs to transistors, so gate is the control element.",
"A-002-005-007": "The SCR belongs to the thyristor family, the group of latching four-layer switching devices. Phase-locked loops, varactors, and varistors are unrelated device classes, so thyristor is the correct family.",
"A-002-005-008": "In amateur gear the SCR's main use is in a power-supply overvoltage 'crowbar' circuit: if the voltage rises too high, the SCR fires and shorts the supply to blow a fuse and protect the equipment. Amplifier, preamp, and SWR-detector roles are not typical SCR applications.",
"A-002-005-009": "The device with anode, cathode, and gate terminals is the SCR. Bipolar transistors use base/collector/emitter and FETs use gate/source/drain, so only the SCR has that exact terminal set.",
"A-002-005-010": "Gated 'on,' the SCR latches and conducts with a small forward drop, just like a forward-biased silicon rectifier. The reverse-biased options describe the blocking, non-conducting state, which is the opposite of being gated on.",
"A-002-005-011": "The SCR is the PNPN (four-layer) device among the choices, which gives it its latching action. The PIN, Schottky, and Zener diodes are all two-layer junction devices, so they are not PNPN.",
"A-002-006-001": "A Class A amplifier is biased so the device conducts for the entire 360-degree cycle, never cutting off. This gives the best linearity but the lowest efficiency, which is the trade-off that defines Class A.",
"A-002-006-002": "Class A conducts over the whole cycle, so it reproduces the waveform most faithfully, giving the highest linearity and least distortion. The trade-off is poor efficiency, but for low distortion Class A wins over AB, B, and C.",
"A-002-006-003": "A Class AB amplifier conducts for more than 180 degrees but less than the full 360, a compromise between Class A (full cycle) and Class B (half cycle). This improves efficiency over Class A while keeping distortion lower than Class B.",
"A-002-006-004": "A Class B amplifier conducts for exactly 180 degrees, half of each cycle, with the device cutting off for the other half. Two devices in push-pull each handle one half so the full waveform is reconstructed; less than 180 degrees would be Class C.",
"A-002-006-005": "A Class C amplifier conducts for less than 180 degrees, only a portion of each cycle, which makes it very efficient but highly distorting. A tuned output circuit restores the sine wave, so Class C suits constant-amplitude (FM, CW) signals rather than linear amplification.",
"A-002-006-006": "Class C conducts for the shortest part of the cycle (less than 180 degrees), so the device spends most of the time off and dissipates little power, giving the highest efficiency. Efficiency rises as conduction angle shrinks, so Class A (full cycle) is the least efficient.",
"A-002-006-007": "CW, RTTY, and FM are constant-amplitude (non-linear) modes, so they tolerate the distortion of a Class C stage, which offers the highest efficiency. Linear modes like SSB would need Class AB, but for these modes Class C is the efficient choice.",
"A-002-006-008": "Class A conducts over the entire cycle, so the device always dissipates power, giving the least efficiency of all classes. Efficiency improves as conduction angle decreases toward Class C, so Class A is the lowest.",
"A-002-006-009": "Class C conducts for the smallest part of the cycle, so it reproduces only a sliver of the waveform, giving the poorest linearity and most distortion. It relies on a tuned circuit to rebuild the signal, so it is unsuitable for linear modes like SSB.",
"A-002-006-010": "Class A is the amplifier that operates over the full 360-degree cycle without cutting off. Class AB conducts more than half, Class B exactly half, and Class C less than half, so only Class A covers the whole cycle.",
"A-002-006-011": "Class C is the amplifier that conducts for less than 180 degrees of the cycle, the shortest conduction angle. Class B conducts exactly 180 degrees and Class AB more than that, so only Class C operates over less than half a cycle.",
"A-002-007-001": "In a common-source FET amplifier the gate draws essentially no current, so the input impedance is set almost entirely by the external gate biasing resistor network. The source-drain and substrate resistances do not set the input impedance, so those distractors are wrong.",
"A-002-007-002": "The output of a common-source FET stage is taken at the drain, so its output impedance is set chiefly by the drain (load) resistor. Supply voltages and the input impedance do not determine the output impedance, making those choices incorrect.",
"A-002-007-003": "A Darlington pair (two transistors with combined gain) offers very high current gain, high input impedance, and low output impedance, ideal for driving loads from a weak source. The wording about 'mutual inductance' is nonsense for a DC-coupled transistor pair, so those distractors are wrong.",
"A-002-007-004": "A common-base amplifier does not invert: its output is in phase with its input. The 180-degree (inverting) result belongs to the common-emitter stage, so that is the tempting wrong answer for the common-base configuration.",
"A-002-007-005": "The common-base amplifier has a very low input impedance (the emitter input) compared with its high output impedance (the collector). This impedance step-up is a defining trait, so 'only slightly' higher or lower understates the large difference.",
"A-002-007-006": "The common-emitter amplifier inverts the signal, so input and output are 180 degrees out of phase. Common-base and common-collector stages are non-inverting (in phase), so this 180-degree inversion is unique to the common-emitter.",
"A-002-007-007": "The common-collector (emitter-follower) amplifier is non-inverting, so its output is in phase with its input, just following it with near-unity voltage gain. Only the common-emitter inverts by 180 degrees, so that distractor does not apply here.",
"A-002-007-008": "The source-follower is just another name for the common-drain FET circuit, where the output is taken at the source and follows the gate voltage with near-unity gain. Common-source and common-gate are different configurations, so they are wrong here.",
"A-002-007-009": "The common-source FET stage parallels the common-emitter bipolar stage: both invert the signal and provide good voltage gain. Common-collector and common-base behave differently, so common-emitter is the matching bipolar circuit.",
"A-002-007-010": "The common-drain (source-follower) FET stage corresponds to the common-collector (emitter-follower) bipolar stage: both are non-inverting buffers with near-unity voltage gain and low output impedance. So common-collector is the correct match.",
"A-002-007-011": "The common-gate FET stage corresponds to the common-base bipolar stage: both are non-inverting with low input impedance and are useful at high frequencies. So common-base is the matching configuration.",
"A-002-008-001": "An operational amplifier is a high-gain, direct-coupled differential amplifier whose behaviour is set by the external components (the feedback network) you add around it. Its gain is not fixed by internal parts, and it is not just an audio amplifier or a software routine, so those distractors are wrong.",
"A-002-008-002": "The ideal op-amp has infinite input impedance (draws no input current), zero output impedance (drives any load), infinite gain, and flat frequency response. Any option with zero input or infinite output impedance describes the opposite of ideal behaviour.",
"A-002-008-003": "In a closed-loop op-amp the external feedback network sets the gain, because the op-amp's own huge open-loop gain is tamed by feedback to a precise, predictable value. The supply voltage and internal PNP details do not set the closed-loop gain, so those are distractors.",
"A-002-008-004": "Offset voltage is the small input voltage difference that would be needed to make the output exactly zero, measured in the open-loop condition because of slight internal imbalance. It is not a closed-loop measurement or an output-minus-input figure, so those options miss the definition.",
"A-002-008-005": "An ideal op-amp draws no input current, which means its input impedance is very high (ideally infinite). Fixed values like 100 or 1000 ohms describe real resistors, not the ideal op-amp's near-infinite input impedance.",
"A-002-008-006": "An ideal op-amp can drive any load without losing voltage, so its output impedance is very low (ideally zero). Specific values like 100 or 1000 ohms are not characteristics of the ideal device.",
"A-002-008-007": "Op-amp active filters provide gain instead of the insertion loss of passive LC filters, so the signal can come out stronger rather than weaker. Op-amps also avoid bulky inductors, but the key listed advantage over LC is gain rather than loss.",
"A-002-008-008": "In amateur gear op-amp RC active filters are mainly used as audio filters in receivers, for example to sharpen CW or SSB passbands. They are not used for power-supply smoothing or as RF high/low-pass filters, since op-amps work at audio, not RF, frequencies.",
"A-002-008-009": "An inverting op-amp circuit feeds the signal to the inverting input so the output is 180 degrees out of phase with the input. In-phase operation is the non-inverting configuration, so that is the tempting opposite answer.",
"A-002-008-010": "A non-inverting op-amp circuit produces an output that is in phase with the input, feeding the signal to the non-inverting input. The 180-degrees-out-of-phase option describes the inverting configuration instead, so it is the distractor to avoid.",
"A-002-008-011": "A high-gain, direct-coupled differential amplifier whose characteristics are set by external components is, by definition, an operational amplifier. Difference, summing, and plain high-gain audio amplifiers are narrower or different terms, so 'operational amplifier' is the best fit.",
"A-002-009-001": "Mixing combines two signals in a non-linear device to produce new sum and difference frequencies, the heart of frequency conversion in receivers and transmitters. Recovering intelligence is detection, and the noise-elimination options describe other processes, so they are wrong.",
"A-002-009-002": "A mixer's output contains the two original input frequencies plus their sum and difference frequencies. The 1.414/0.707 and square-root options are not how mixing works, so the original-plus-sum-and-difference answer is correct.",
"A-002-009-003": "Too much signal drives the mixer beyond its linear range, generating unwanted spurious signals (intermodulation products) and 'birdies.' This overload does not produce helpful limiting or a clean beat note, so spurious signals is the right consequence.",
"A-002-009-004": "A series capacitor passes the RF input signal while blocking the DC bias, so it acts as a DC blocking (coupling) capacitor at the base. It is not part of the tuned circuit here nor a bypass to ground, since it is in the signal path, not across it.",
"A-002-009-005": "A frequency multiplier needs a harmonic-rich output, so it is run in Class C, whose short conduction angle and heavy distortion generate strong harmonics that a tuned circuit then selects. The more linear classes (A, AB, B) produce too few harmonics to multiply efficiently.",
"A-002-009-006": "The variable capacitor C2 forms a resonant tank with L1, and adjusting it tunes that tank to the desired harmonic (multiple) of the input frequency so only that harmonic is selected. Tuning to the input frequency or providing feedback would defeat the multiplier's purpose.",
"A-002-009-007": "C3 connects the supply end of L1 to ground for RF, providing an RF ground at the VCC connection point so the supply line looks like ground to the signal. It does not resonate with L1 or bypass audio; its job is to keep RF out of the power supply.",
"A-002-009-008": "L1 with the variable capacitor C2 forms the resonant output tank that selects the chosen harmonic, making the stage act as a frequency multiplier. It is not a divider, voltage divider, or doubler in the DC sense; it is a tuned circuit picking a higher harmonic.",
"A-002-009-009": "If a circuit's tuned components resonate at a higher frequency than the signal applied to it, it is selecting a harmonic, which is the signature of a frequency multiplier. A plain amplifier or linear stage stays on the same frequency, so the higher-frequency tuning points to multiplication.",
"A-002-009-010": "C3 ties the supply end of L1 to ground for RF, so it functions as an RF bypass capacitor keeping signal energy out of the power supply. It is in shunt (to ground), not in the signal path, so it is not a DC-blocking, coupling, or tuning capacitor.",
"A-002-009-011": "A mixer combines the input with a local oscillator to produce a sum or difference, allowing a shift from 5.3 MHz to 14.3 MHz (which is not an integer multiple). A frequency multiplier can only reach integer multiples, and 14.3 is not a whole-number multiple of 5.3, so a mixer is needed.",
"A-002-010-001": "A NAND gate is an AND followed by an inverter, so its output goes low (logic 0) only when every input is high (logic 1); for all other input combinations the output is 1. The option giving 1 only when all inputs are 1 describes a plain AND gate, so that is the tempting wrong answer.",
"A-002-010-002": "An OR gate outputs logic 1 if any input is logic 1; it is only 0 when all inputs are 0. The options that require all inputs the same describe AND or NOR behaviour, so 'any input high gives 1' is the OR rule.",
"A-002-010-003": "A NOR gate is an OR followed by an inverter, so its output is 0 if any or all inputs are 1, and only goes to 1 when every input is 0. The option giving 0 only when all inputs are 0 is backwards, so watch the inversion.",
"A-002-010-004": "A NOT gate (inverter) has one input and flips its logic level, so a logic 1 input gives a logic 0 output. The data-transmission descriptions are about gating, not inversion, so the simple level-flip definition is correct.",
"A-002-010-005": "An EXCLUSIVE OR (XOR) gate outputs logic 1 only when its inputs differ, i.e. when one and only one input is 1. If both inputs are 1 or both are 0 the output is 0, so the 'all inputs 1' option describes an AND, not an XOR.",
"A-002-010-006": "An EXCLUSIVE NOR (XNOR) gate is the inverse of XOR, so it outputs logic 1 when its inputs are the same, including when all inputs are 1. The option giving 1 for a single 1 input describes XOR behaviour, the opposite, so it is the distractor.",
"A-002-010-007": "An AND gate outputs logic 1 only when all of its inputs are logic 1; any 0 input forces the output to 0. The options that give 1 from a single 1 or from all 0s describe OR or NOR behaviour, so they are wrong.",
"A-002-010-008": "A flip-flop is a binary sequential logic element with two stable states, holding a single bit of memory until clocked or set. 'Binary' means two states, so the four-, eight-, or one-state options contradict the definition.",
"A-002-010-009": "A bistable multivibrator has two stable states and is exactly what we call a flip-flop. Astable and monostable multivibrators give clocks and one-shots, but the bistable form is the flip-flop, so the gate options are wrong.",
"A-002-010-010": "A latch is another name for a flip-flop, a one-bit memory element that holds (latches) its state. A decade counter is built from flip-flops but is not itself a latch, and an OR gate or op-amp store nothing, so flip-flop is correct.",
"A-002-010-011": "In a multivibrator the two transistors alternate, so when one conducts (saturates) the cross-coupling drives the other into cut-off (off). 'Saturated' describes the conducting transistor, not the other one, so cut off is the correct state of the partner.",
"A-002-011-001": "A crystal lattice filter uses several quartz crystals arranged so their combined high-Q response gives a narrow bandwidth with steep (sharp) skirts, ideal for selecting one SSB or CW signal. Wide-bandwidth or shallow-skirt descriptions miss the point of using crystals, which is sharpness.",
"A-002-011-002": "The bandwidth and response shape of a crystal lattice filter are set by the relative frequencies of the individual crystals; spacing them apart widens the passband and changes the skirt shape. The centre frequency, following gain, and signal amplitude do not determine the filter's shape.",
"A-002-011-003": "A good SSB voice filter passes about 2.4 kHz, just enough for intelligible speech while rejecting adjacent signals. 500 Hz is for CW, while 6 kHz or 15 kHz are far too wide for SSB and would let in interference, so 2.4 kHz is correct.",
"A-002-011-004": "A crystal oscillator's quartz element has an extremely high Q and a very precise mechanical resonance, giving it much greater frequency stability than a tuned LC oscillator. Simplicity and harmonic behaviour are not its advantage; rock-solid frequency stability is.",
"A-002-011-005": "A quartz crystal has an enormously high Q (thousands), far higher than any LC circuit, which is why it makes such a sharp, narrow bandpass filter. A low-Q crystal or a high-Q LC circuit would not give that selectivity, so the crystal's high Q is the reason.",
"A-002-011-006": "The piezoelectric effect means a voltage appears when certain crystals are mechanically deformed (and they flex when a voltage is applied). Magnets and impurities have nothing to do with piezoelectricity, so 'deforming certain crystals' is the correct cause.",
"A-002-011-007": "Electrically a quartz crystal behaves like a very high Q tuned (resonant) LC circuit, which is why it gives such sharp selectivity and stable oscillation. It is not a variable capacitance or a low-Q circuit; its hallmark is its extremely high Q.",
"A-002-011-008": "An overtone oscillator deliberately operates the crystal near an integral multiple (overtone) of its fundamental frequency to reach higher frequencies directly. A crystal multiplier multiplies after oscillation, while lattice and ladder are filter types, so overtone oscillator is correct.",
"A-002-011-009": "Crystals give excellent frequency stability, accuracy, and low noise because of their high Q, but they cannot deliver high power output, so high power output is the property that does not apply. The crystal is a frequency-determining element, not a power source.",
"A-002-011-010": "Crystal oscillators, filters, and crystal microphones all rely on the piezoelectric effect, the link between mechanical deformation and voltage in certain crystals. Ferro-resonance and the made-up 'Hertzberg' and 'overtone' effects do not explain all three devices, so piezoelectric is correct.",
"A-002-011-011": "Crystals are used in oscillators, lattice filters, and microphones, but not in active filters, which are built from op-amps and RC networks instead. So 'active filters' is the application where crystals do not apply.",
"A-002-012-001": "The three general filter groupings by what band they pass are high-pass, low-pass, and band-pass. Hartley/Colpitts/Pierce are oscillator types, and the other lists name circuit elements, not filter categories, so high/low/band-pass is correct.",
"A-002-012-002": "A Butterworth filter is designed for a maximally flat response across its passband, with no ripple, at the cost of a more gradual cutoff. The constant-impedance-product description fits a constant-k filter, and the conductor/capacitor-only claims are wrong, so maximally flat is the defining feature.",
"A-002-012-003": "A Chebyshev filter trades allowable ripple in the passband for a sharper, steeper cutoff than a Butterworth. The ripple-with-sharp-cutoff description fits Chebyshev specifically, while Butterworth is flat with a gentler roll-off, so it is the distractor.",
"A-002-012-004": "A Chebyshev filter deliberately allows ripple in the passband in exchange for steeper skirts (faster cutoff) than a Butterworth. The maximally-flat description belongs to the Butterworth, and the inductor/capacitor-only claims are wrong, so the ripple-for-steepness trade is its hallmark.",
"A-002-012-005": "Resonant cavities act as very high-Q, narrow bandpass filters at VHF and higher frequencies, where their physical size is practical. They are not used as power-line, low-pass, or high-pass filters, so the narrow VHF bandpass role is correct.",
"A-002-012-006": "A quarter-wavelength cavity is one quarter of the free-space wavelength: λ = 300 / f(MHz) = 300 / 50 = 6 metres, so λ/4 = 6 / 4 = 1.5 metres (about 5 ft). The other lengths come from using the wrong fraction of a wavelength, so divide the wavelength by four.",
"A-002-012-007": "A helical resonator is a compact high-Q tuned circuit installed in a receiver front end to cut overload and spurious responses at VHF, UHF, and above. A diplexer, directional coupler, or duplexer route or sample signals rather than filtering the front end, so helical resonator is correct.",
"A-002-012-008": "A television channel is about 6 MHz wide, which is far too broad for a high-Q resonant cavity (those give very narrow passbands) yet awkward for Butterworth or Chebyshev LC filters at VHF and above. Since no single listed filter is a good fit for that wide a bandwidth at these frequencies, the correct answer is 'none of the other answers.'",
"A-002-012-009": "The Butterworth filter's primary advantage is its maximally flat response across the passband, with no ripple. The ripple-for-steeper-skirts trait belongs to the Chebyshev, so it is the opposite and a tempting distractor.",
"A-002-012-010": "The Chebyshev filter's primary advantage over Butterworth is steeper skirts (faster cutoff), achieved by allowing some ripple in the passband. The maximally-flat response is the Butterworth's trait, so it is the opposite and the distractor to avoid.",
"A-002-012-011": "A cavity filter relies on physical resonance whose size is only practical at VHF and above, so it is not suitable at audio and low radio frequencies. Elliptical, Chebyshev, and Butterworth filters can all be built with lumped components for low frequencies, so the cavity is the odd one out.",
"A-003-001-001": "On an oscilloscope you see the full vertical extent of the trace directly, so the easiest reading is from the bottom of the wave to the top, which is the peak-to-peak voltage. Peak and RMS require you to find the centre line or do a 0.707 conversion, and average is not shown at all, so each of those takes an extra step.",
"A-003-001-002": "For a pure sine wave, RMS = peak × 0.707, and peak = half the peak-to-peak. Here peak = 340 ÷ 2 = 170 V, so RMS = 170 × 0.707 ≈ 120 V. The tempting distractor 170 V is the peak value, not the RMS value.",
"A-003-001-003": "RMS (root-mean-square) is defined by heating effect: it is the AC voltage that delivers the same power to a resistor as a DC voltage of equal value. The wrong answers either compare AC to the peak (not RMS) or invent a 'square root of peak' rule, but RMS comes from averaging the square of the waveform, not from a simple square root.",
"A-003-001-004": "For a sine wave RMS = peak × 0.707. With a peak of 20 V, RMS = 20 × 0.707 ≈ 14.14 V. The frequency (100 Hz) is irrelevant to the conversion; 28.28 V would be peak-to-peak and 7.07 V comes from dividing instead of multiplying.",
"A-003-001-005": "Ohm's law for AC normally uses RMS values, and RMS = peak × 0.707, so 'peak values times 0.707' is correct. Average values do not give true power and would mislead Ohm's-law calculations, which is why the average-based options are wrong.",
"A-003-001-006": "The effective (RMS) value of a sine wave is peak × 0.707, i.e. 70.7% of the maximum. The distractor 63.6% is the average value of a rectified sine (2/π), a common trap, so do not confuse average with effective.",
"A-003-001-007": "AC voltmeters are calibrated in RMS because RMS is the value used for power and Ohm's-law work and matches how AC mains is rated. They do not display peak, instantaneous, or average values, even though the internal sensor may actually respond to average and be scaled to read RMS.",
"A-003-001-008": "Effective value and RMS mean the same thing, and AC voltmeters are scaled to read it because RMS is what determines heating and power. Peak, peak-to-peak, and average are larger or smaller scalings of the same waveform and are not what the meter is set up to show.",
"A-003-001-009": "By definition, the RMS value of an AC voltage produces the same heating in a resistor as an equal DC voltage. Peak and peak-to-peak are larger numbers that overstate the heating, and average understates it, so only RMS gives the true equivalent power.",
"A-003-001-010": "Work outward from RMS: peak = RMS × 1.414, then peak-to-peak = 2 × peak. So peak = 120 × 1.414 ≈ 169.7 V, and peak-to-peak = 2 × 169.7 ≈ 339.5 V. The distractor 169.7 V is only the peak, missing the final doubling.",
"A-003-001-011": "For a sine wave RMS = peak × 0.707. With a 17 V peak, RMS = 17 × 0.707 ≈ 12 V. The value 34 V would be peak-to-peak (twice the peak), not the RMS.",
"A-003-002-001": "Peak-envelope power (PEP) is the average power over one RF cycle at the highest crest of the modulation envelope. It is the standard way amateur output power is specified for SSB; carrier power and mean power are lower figures that do not capture the modulation peak.",
"A-003-002-002": "Multiplying peak-envelope voltage by 0.707 gives the RMS voltage, and RMS² ÷ R is power, so this procedure yields PEP (peak-envelope power). PIV is a diode voltage rating and ERP is radiated power, so neither comes from this voltage-and-resistance calculation.",
"A-003-002-003": "PEP is found from voltage and resistance: take peak-envelope voltage × 0.707 to get RMS, square it, and divide by the load resistance (P = V²RMS / R). It is a real, measurable quantity, not hypothetical, and 'peak voltage × peak current' overstates the true average power at the crest.",
"A-003-002-004": "With only a voltmeter you measure voltage across a known resistive load, so the power formula is P = E² / R. The forms P = EI/R and P = IR are dimensionally wrong for power, and P = EI cos θ needs current and a phase angle you cannot get from a voltmeter alone.",
"A-003-002-005": "Using a scope you read peak-envelope voltage (PEV), convert to RMS with 0.707, then apply P = V²RMS / RL, giving PEP = [(0.707 PEV)(0.707 PEV)] / RL. The options using Vp directly or 1.414 omit the RMS conversion and would give the wrong power.",
"A-003-002-006": "First convert: peak = 200 ÷ 2 = 100 V, then RMS = 100 × 0.707 ≈ 70.7 V. PEP = V²RMS / R = 70.7² / 50 ≈ 5000 / 50 = 100 W. Forgetting to halve the peak-to-peak or to apply 0.707 is what produces the larger wrong answers.",
"A-003-002-007": "Peak = 500 ÷ 2 = 250 V, RMS = 250 × 0.707 ≈ 176.8 V, and PEP = V²RMS / R = 176.8² / 50 ≈ 31250 / 50 = 625 W. A shortcut is PEP = (Vpp)² / (8R) = 500² / 400 = 625 W, which folds the halving and 0.707 into one step.",
"A-003-002-008": "For an unmodulated carrier the signal is a steady sine wave, so its envelope never rises above the average level and PEP equals the average power. The wattmeter reads 1060 W average, so PEP is also 1060 W; doubling to 2120 W would be wrong because there is no modulation peak.",
"A-003-002-009": "Peak = 400 ÷ 2 = 200 V, RMS = 200 × 0.707 ≈ 141.4 V, and PEP = V²RMS / R = 141.4² / 50 ≈ 20000 / 50 = 400 W. Equivalently (Vpp)² / (8R) = 400² / 400 = 400 W.",
"A-003-002-010": "Peak = 800 ÷ 2 = 400 V, RMS = 400 × 0.707 ≈ 282.8 V, and PEP = V²RMS / R = 282.8² / 50 ≈ 80000 / 50 = 1600 W. The quick form (Vpp)² / (8R) = 800² / 400 = 1600 W gives the same result.",
"A-003-002-011": "For an unmodulated carrier the average power equals the PEP, since the envelope is flat. Peak = 500 ÷ 2 = 250 V, RMS = 250 × 0.707 ≈ 176.8 V, so power = 176.8² / 50 ≈ 625 W, which is what an average-reading meter would show.",
"A-003-003-001": "A dip meter is essentially a variable-frequency oscillator whose feedback (oscillation) current is shown on a meter. When its coil is coupled to a resonant circuit, that circuit absorbs energy at resonance and the meter current 'dips', which is how the device gets its name.",
"A-003-003-002": "A dip meter indicates the resonant frequency of a circuit: the meter reading dips when the oscillator is tuned to the circuit's resonance. It is only approximate, so the answers claiming it accurately measures power, field strength, or frequency are wrong.",
"A-003-003-003": "A dip meter checks resonance, so its two useful station jobs are finding the resonant frequency of antenna traps and of any tuned LC circuit. It cannot measure impedance or percentage modulation, which rules out the other pairings.",
"A-003-003-004": "The dip meter's oscillator supplies RF energy that a nearby resonant circuit absorbs, letting you find that circuit's resonant frequency from the dip. Tasks like calibrating a wavemeter, judging impedance mismatch, or adjusting an inductor are not what the dip itself reveals.",
"A-003-003-005": "A dip meter shows resonance and rough frequency, but it cannot directly read out an actual capacitance or inductance value in farads or henrys. It can still align tuned circuits and indicate oscillation frequency, so measuring component values is the task it cannot do directly.",
"A-003-003-006": "A signal generator's output attenuator dial is only accurate when the attenuator is properly terminated in its design impedance. With the wrong load the impedance match is off and the indicated output no longer reflects the true level.",
"A-003-003-007": "A signal generator is a high-stability oscillator producing a controllable, wide range of frequencies and amplitudes for testing receivers and circuits. Low-stability sweep or injection oscillators are different tools, and a device giving signals only at fixed exact intervals is a marker generator, not a signal generator.",
"A-003-003-008": "A dip meter should be coupled loosely to the circuit under test; over-coupling pulls the indicated frequency away from true resonance and broadens the dip. It is not limited to series circuits and it does not measure frequency accurately, so loose coupling is the correct practice.",
"A-003-003-009": "Measuring 12 dB SINAD needs a calibrated RF signal generator with FM tone modulation to feed the receiver, and a distortion (THD) analyzer to measure the signal-plus-noise-plus-distortion to noise-plus-distortion ratio at the audio output. A deviation meter or noise bridge does not measure SINAD, so those pairings are wrong.",
"A-003-003-010": "A dip meter works by detecting energy absorbed at resonance, which is most pronounced in a parallel tuned circuit (high impedance at resonance) coupled to its coil. Series circuits do not present the same easily-coupled resonant behaviour, so the dip meter applies most directly to parallel tuned circuits.",
"A-003-003-011": "A dip meter senses a separate circuit's resonance, so the transmitter's own power output has no effect on its frequency accuracy. Hand capacity, stray capacity, and over-coupling all shift the indicated frequency, so the transmitter power is the one factor that does not.",
"A-003-004-001": "A frequency counter makes frequency measurements by counting the cycles of an input signal over a precise time interval. It does not measure deviation, generate noise, or produce a reference; it simply counts and displays frequency.",
"A-003-004-002": "A counter's performance is set by its time base accuracy and time base stability (which fix how accurately it counts) and by the speed of its logic (which sets the highest frequency it can handle). The number of display digits only affects resolution, not the underlying accuracy or frequency response, so options citing it are wrong.",
"A-003-004-003": "Because a counter compares the input against its internal time base, improving the accuracy of that time base directly improves measurement accuracy. Faster or slower logic changes the frequency range it can handle, not the basic accuracy, so upgrading the time base is the key.",
"A-003-004-004": "Error = reading × accuracy in parts per million. Here 146 520 000 Hz × 0.1 ÷ 1 000 000 = 146 520 000 × 10⁻⁷ = 14.652 Hz. The trap answers come from using the wrong power of ten when converting PPM.",
"A-003-004-005": "Error = reading × PPM ÷ 1 000 000 = 146 520 000 × 10 ÷ 1 000 000 = 146 520 000 × 10⁻⁵ = 1465.2 Hz. This is 100 times the 0.1 PPM case, so watch the decimal point when scaling PPM.",
"A-003-004-006": "A frequency counter's clock (time base) is normally a crystal oscillator because quartz crystals are very stable and accurate. Tuning forks, Hartley oscillators, and free-running multivibrators drift far too much to serve as a reliable time base.",
"A-003-004-007": "The accuracy of a counter is determined by its internal time-base generator, since every count is referenced to that clock. Physical size, display type, and digit count affect resolution or convenience but not the fundamental accuracy.",
"A-003-004-008": "A frequency-marker generator uses a stable low-frequency crystal oscillator rich in harmonics, producing markers at regular intervals across the band to calibrate a receiver dial. A plain signal generator or frequency counter does not place evenly spaced reference markers across the dial in this way.",
"A-003-004-009": "The traditional check is to zero-beat the crystal calibrator against a known standard-frequency broadcast such as WWV, listening for the beat note to drop to zero as the frequencies match. Comparing it with your own transmitter or receiver only checks against an equally uncertain source, so it cannot verify true accuracy.",
"A-003-004-010": "A VCXO is deliberately made tunable by an applied voltage, which means its frequency moves and it is not, on its own, a high-stability reference. The TCXO, OCXO, and GPSDO are all designed for high stability, so the voltage-controlled VCXO is the odd one out.",
"A-003-004-011": "To calibrate against WWV you tune for zero-beat, making the beat tone's frequency as low as possible with as long a period as possible; at true zero-beat the tone disappears entirely. Aiming for a high audio tone or a combined/mean frequency would leave a frequency offset rather than a match.",
"A-003-005-001": "Lissajous patterns form loops in the ratio of the two frequencies. With 100 Hz horizontal and 150 Hz vertical the ratio is 2:3, giving 3 horizontal loops and 2 vertical loops. The screen shows frequency ratios, not millimetre dimensions, so the size-based answers are wrong.",
"A-003-005-002": "An oscilloscope's accuracy and frequency response are limited by the accuracy of its time base and by the linearity and bandwidth of its deflection (vertical and horizontal) amplifiers. The other options invent properties like 'tube face increments' that are not the real limiting factors.",
"A-003-005-003": "Frequency response is set mainly by the vertical amplifier, so raising the vertical amplifier's frequency response (and the horizontal sweep rate so fast signals fit on screen) improves it. Using a crystal time base improves accuracy, not bandwidth, so those options miss the point.",
"A-003-005-004": "Displaying input and output simultaneously requires a dual-trace oscilloscope, which has two vertical channels sharing one time base. Putting input on X and output on Y instead produces a Lissajous figure, not two separate waveforms over time.",
"A-003-005-005": "An oscilloscope shows voltage versus time, so it cannot directly read out a frequency in hertz; you must derive it from the period. It can display DC voltage, complex waveform amplitudes, and (via the deflection method) FM deviation, so measuring frequency directly is the task it cannot do.",
"A-003-005-006": "An oscilloscope's bandwidth is the highest-frequency signal it can faithfully display, set chiefly by its vertical amplifier. It is not the time-base accuracy or screen persistence; above the bandwidth, signals appear reduced in amplitude and distorted.",
"A-003-005-007": "When two signals are exactly in phase (0°) or exactly out of phase (180°), the Lissajous figure collapses to a diagonal straight line. A phase difference near 90° opens it into an ellipse or circle, so the straight diagonal line specifically signals 0° or 180°.",
"A-003-005-008": "In a Lissajous pattern the loops are inversely proportional to frequency: f_vertical / f_horizontal = horizontal loops / vertical loops. So f_vertical = 100 kHz × 2 ÷ 5 = 40 kHz. The 5 vertical loops correspond to the horizontal frequency and vice versa, which is the easy part to mix up.",
"A-003-005-009": "A scope probe must be compensated whenever it is used with a different oscilloscope, because compensation matches the probe's capacitance to that specific scope's input. An uncompensated probe distorts square waves; it is not tied to sine waves, varying frequency, or adding a series resistor.",
"A-003-005-010": "An oscilloscope is the best instrument for checking the quality of a CW or SSB signal because it shows the actual waveform and modulation envelope, revealing flat-topping, distortion, or key clicks. A sidetone monitor or field-strength meter only confirms a signal is present, not its quality.",
"A-003-005-011": "To check transmitted signal quality you feed the vertical input from a sample of the transmitter's actual RF output taken through a sampling device (such as a coupler on the line). Audio input, a nearby antenna, or a receiver's IF would not show the true outgoing RF waveform.",
"A-003-006-001": "A shunt carries the extra current the meter cannot. At full scale the meter drops V = 40 µA × 96 Ω = 3840 µV, and the shunt must carry 1 mA − 40 µA = 960 µA. So R_shunt = 3840 µV ÷ 960 µA = 4 Ω.",
"A-003-006-002": "To make a voltmeter, the total resistance must limit current to full scale at the desired voltage: R_total = 20 V ÷ 1 mA = 20 000 Ω. Subtract the meter's own 0.5 Ω, giving a series (multiplier) resistance of 19 999.5 Ω. It must be in series, not shunt, since a voltmeter needs high resistance.",
"A-003-006-003": "The meter reaches full scale at I = 150 V ÷ 150 000 Ω = 1 mA. For 750 V the total resistance must be 750 V ÷ 1 mA = 750 000 Ω, so the added multiplier is 750 000 − 150 000 = 600 000 Ω in series.",
"A-003-006-004": "An ammeter's sensitivity is the current that causes full-scale deflection, the smallest current that drives the needle fully across. The meter's resistance, loading effect, and shunt value are related properties but are not what 'sensitivity' specifically means.",
"A-003-006-005": "Voltmeter sensitivity in ohms per volt is the reciprocal of the full-scale current of the movement: I = 1 ÷ 20 000 Ω/V = 50 × 10⁻⁶ A = 50 µA. So a 20 kΩ/V meter uses a 50 microampere movement; higher ohms-per-volt means a more sensitive (smaller current) meter.",
"A-003-006-006": "Sensitivity in ohms per volt is the total resistance divided by the full-scale voltage of that range: 150 000 Ω ÷ 150 V = 1000 ohms per volt. This corresponds to a 1 mA movement (1 ÷ 1000).",
"A-003-006-007": "To extend a DC ammeter's range you add a low-value shunt resistor in parallel with the meter so it diverts most of the extra current. A series resistor would instead turn it toward a voltmeter, and changing inductance or capacitance is irrelevant to DC current measurement.",
"A-003-006-008": "On a multimeter, each higher voltage range needs more series (multiplier) resistance to keep the movement at full scale, so switching up adds resistance in series with the meter. Voltmeter multipliers are always in series, so the parallel-resistance options are wrong.",
"A-003-006-009": "An ammeter's range is increased by adding a shunt resistance in parallel with the meter, which bypasses the excess current around the movement. Adding resistance in series would reduce current and act like a voltmeter multiplier, not extend the ammeter range.",
"A-003-006-010": "For the most accurate output-power reading, an RF wattmeter belongs right at the transmitter output connector, before line losses and standing waves alter the measurement. Readings taken part-way down the line or at the antenna feed point are affected by feedline loss and SWR.",
"A-003-006-011": "Most RF wattmeters are designed for a 50 Ω line impedance, matching the standard impedance of amateur coax and transmitter outputs. Using them on a different impedance would give inaccurate readings, so 50 Ω is the usual operating value.",
"A-004-001-001": "The bridge and the full-wave centre-tap both use both halves of the AC cycle, but the bridge applies the whole secondary winding to the load each half-cycle. The centre-tap rectifier only uses half the winding at a time, so for the same total secondary voltage its output is about half. That is why the bridge gives the highest average output voltage for a given secondary.",
"A-004-001-002": "With a capacitor input filter and almost no load, the capacitor charges to the peak voltage (1.414 × RMS) and holds it. On the next half-cycle the diode sees that stored peak plus the opposite peak of the source, so the peak inverse voltage reaches about 2 × 1.414 = 2.8 times the RMS voltage. The distractor 1.4 is only the single peak, which ignores the capacitor's stored charge adding on top.",
"A-004-001-003": "In a full-wave centre-tap supply the non-conducting diode sees the peak across the whole secondary while the other diode conducts, so its reverse voltage equals the full peak-to-peak swing. That is 2 × (1.414 × RMS) = 2.8 times the RMS voltage, and unlike the half-wave case this holds regardless of load. The values 0.636 and 0.707 are average and RMS factors of a sine wave, not the PIV.",
"A-004-001-004": "A bridge rectifier uses four diodes arranged so the full secondary winding feeds the load on both half-cycles, so it does not need the transformer secondary to be split with a centre tap. The centre-tap design must have that tap because each diode only handles one half of the winding. Removing the centre-tap requirement is the bridge's key practical advantage.",
"A-004-001-005": "The bridge uses the entire secondary winding on each half-cycle, while the centre-tap rectifier uses only half the winding at a time, so for the same transformer the bridge delivers about double the output voltage. The catch is that the centre-tap design effectively wastes half its winding, which the bridge avoids. Hence the bridge output is double, not the same or half.",
"A-004-001-006": "A full-wave rectifier produces one output pulse for each half of the AC cycle, so the ripple frequency is twice the line frequency. Canadian household power is 60 Hz, so the ripple is 2 × 60 = 120 Hz. The higher ripple frequency is also easier to filter than the 60 Hz of a half-wave supply.",
"A-004-001-007": "A half-wave rectifier passes only one half of each AC cycle, so it produces just one pulse per cycle and the ripple frequency equals the line frequency. With 60 Hz household power the ripple is therefore 60 Hz. This is the opposite of the full-wave case, where two pulses per cycle give 120 Hz ripple.",
"A-004-001-008": "A full-wave voltage doubler charges capacitors on both halves of the AC waveform and stacks their voltages to roughly double the peak input. Because it works on both half-cycles, its ripple frequency is twice that of a half-wave doubler and it filters more easily. It does not produce four times the voltage; doubling is the whole point.",
"A-004-001-009": "A rectifier diode fails if too much reverse voltage breaks it down or too much forward current overheats it, so the two ratings you must not exceed are peak inverse voltage and average forward current. These directly correspond to the two ways a diode is stressed in a supply. The other choices mix in irrelevant parameters like capacitive reactance that do not describe diode limits.",
"A-004-001-010": "When diodes are stacked in series for high voltage, small differences in their characteristics make them share reverse voltage unequally. A resistor across each diode equalizes the static voltage drops, and a capacitor across each diode bypasses fast transient spikes so no single diode is over-stressed. The aim is voltage equalization and transient protection, not smoothing the output.",
"A-004-001-011": "An unfiltered full-wave rectifier flips both halves of the AC sine wave to the same polarity, producing a train of half-sine humps. Because there are two humps per input cycle, this pulse series occurs at twice the AC input frequency. Without a filter capacitor it is not steady DC; the smoothing only happens once a filter is added.",
"A-004-002-001": "A filter choke must store and pass the DC load current without its iron core saturating, and it must present enough inductance to smooth ripple. So it is rated by inductance (its smoothing ability) and current-handling capacity (before saturation). Breakdown voltage and power loss are not its defining ratings.",
"A-004-002-002": "A choke input filter limits the surge to the capacitor and lets the rectifier conduct more continuously, so the output voltage sags far less between no load and full load. Paired with a full-wave rectifier this gives the best voltage regulation of the choices. A capacitor input filter gives higher voltage but much poorer regulation because output drops sharply as load increases.",
"A-004-002-003": "A capacitor input filter charges to near the peak voltage and holds it, so its main advantage is a higher DC terminal voltage than a choke input filter, which sits closer to the average. The trade-off is poorer regulation and higher peak rectifier currents. So the benefit you gain is the higher output voltage, not better filtering or regulation.",
"A-004-002-004": "A choke input filter conducts current more continuously and limits charging surges, so the output voltage changes little as the load varies. Under a normal load this gives the best-regulated output of the filter types. It does not give the highest voltage; that belongs to the capacitor input filter, which trades away regulation.",
"A-004-002-005": "Power-supply filters are named by which component the rectifier output meets first. If a series choke comes first it is a choke input filter; if a shunt capacitor comes first it is a capacitor input filter. So the two general types are choke input and capacitor input.",
"A-004-002-006": "A bleeder resistor's main job is to safely discharge the filter capacitors after power is removed. Because it always draws a small steady current, it also keeps a minimum load on the supply, which steadies the output voltage and improves voltage regulation. That steadying effect is its useful secondary function.",
"A-004-002-007": "An inductor opposes changes in current, so it presents high reactance to the AC ripple component but very low resistance to steady DC. Placed in series, a choke therefore passes the DC load current freely while impeding the AC ripple. This is exactly the smoothing action wanted from a filter choke.",
"A-004-002-008": "A choke input filter only regulates well when current flows continuously through the choke; below a critical minimum current its behaviour changes and the output voltage jumps up. A bleeder resistor draws a small steady current at all times, guaranteeing that minimum load whenever the supply is on. So the fix is to include a suitable bleeder resistance.",
"A-004-002-009": "The first choke (an inductor) and the first capacitor form an LC pair that can resonate. If their values let them resonate near the ripple frequency, the ripple voltage builds up instead of being smoothed. So these two components, the first choke and first capacitor, must be chosen carefully to keep resonance away from the ripple frequency.",
"A-004-002-010": "If the first choke and first capacitor resonate near the ripple frequency, they form a series resonant circuit whose low impedance lets large currents flow and voltages build up. This can drive excessive rectifier peak current and abnormally high peak inverse voltages on the diodes. Proper component selection keeps this series resonance away from the ripple frequency.",
"A-004-002-011": "Normally the choke input filter holds the capacitor at about nine-tenths of the RMS voltage, but that assumes a load is drawing current. If the bleeder resistor burns out and there is no load, the choke can no longer hold the voltage down and the capacitor charges all the way to the transformer peak voltage. Rating the capacitor for that peak provides the safety margin against this fault condition.",
"A-004-003-001": "A linear regulator works by continuously varying the conduction of its control element (the pass transistor), keeping it partly on so it acts like an automatically adjusted resistor in series with the load. As line voltage or load current changes, its conduction is varied in direct proportion to hold the output steady. Switching the element fully on and off describes a switching regulator instead, which is the tempting wrong answer.",
"A-004-003-002": "A switching regulator rapidly turns its control device fully on and fully off, and it adjusts the duty cycle (the on-versus-off ratio) to suit the line and load conditions. Because the device is either saturated or cut off rather than partly conducting, it dissipates little power and is efficient. Varying conduction in direct proportion describes a linear regulator, not a switcher.",
"A-004-003-003": "A Zener diode held in reverse breakdown maintains a nearly constant voltage across itself over a range of current, making it an ideal stable reference for a linear regulator to compare against. An SCR is a switch, a varactor is a voltage-variable capacitor, and an ordinary junction diode has no sharp regulating point. So the Zener diode is the standard voltage reference.",
"A-004-003-004": "A series regulator places its control element in series with the load and draws only the current the load needs plus a little overhead, so it wastes little of the source. A shunt regulator instead bleeds off excess current continuously, which is less efficient. Where efficient use of the primary power source matters, the series regulator is preferred.",
"A-004-003-005": "A shunt regulator works by diverting more or less current to itself so that the total current drawn from the source stays roughly constant regardless of load. This presents a constant load to the unregulated source, which is exactly the application asked about. A series regulator, by contrast, lets the source current rise and fall with the load.",
"A-004-003-006": "Remote sensing means the regulator's feedback connection to its error amplifier is taken directly at the load rather than at the regulator's own output terminals. This lets the regulator compensate for voltage drop in the wires, holding the voltage constant where it actually matters, at the load. Sensing at the output alone would leave that wiring drop uncorrected.",
"A-004-003-007": "A three-terminal regulator is a complete regulator in one package, containing a voltage reference, an error amplifier, sensing resistors and transistors, and the pass element, with just input, output, and ground pins. It does not supply three different voltages; the name refers to its three terminals. This integration is why such regulators are so simple to use.",
"A-004-003-008": "Besides the range of input voltage it accepts, a three-terminal regulator is specified by the regulated output voltage it produces and the maximum output current it can safely supply. Together these tell you whether it suits your load. Minimum-current figures are not the defining specs, so the correct pair is output voltage and maximum output current.",
"A-004-003-009": "Putting the voltage reference, error amplifier, sensing resistors and transistors, and the pass element all in one package describes the three-terminal regulator. An op-amp, switching, or Zener regulator does not bundle all of those into a single self-contained device with just three pins. This complete integration is the defining feature of the three-terminal type.",
"A-004-003-010": "When very low ripple or tight regulation against current and line swings is needed, a closed-loop amplifier controls the supply, and these electronic regulators fall into two main categories: linear and switching. Linear types vary a pass element's conduction continuously, while switching types chop the power on and off with a controlled duty cycle. So the two categories are linear and switching.",
"A-004-003-011": "A device that packages a reference, a high-gain error amplifier, temperature-compensated sensing resistors and transistors, and a pass element is the familiar three-terminal regulator. The 'three terminal' name comes from its input, output, and common (ground) pins, not from any internal count. The other pin-count names are not standard regulator types.",
"A-004-004-001": "The pass transistor in a series regulator carries the full load current while dropping the difference between its input and output voltage. Power dissipated is voltage across it times current through it, so its dissipation is directly proportional to both the load current and the input/output voltage differential. A large voltage drop combined with high current is what overheats it, which is why heat sinks are needed.",
"A-004-004-002": "Regulation and ripple are best wherever the feedback samples and corrects the voltage, and in a remote-sensed supply the sampling network or error amplifier is connected right at the load. The loop forces that exact point to stay constant and clean. Measuring at the pass transistor output instead leaves any wiring drop beyond it uncorrected.",
"A-004-004-003": "Load resistance here means the equivalent resistance the supply must drive, found from Ohm's law as output voltage divided by the total current it delivers, including the bleeder current. So this is simply the (effective) load resistance of the supply. It is not the rectifier or differential resistance, which describe other things.",
"A-004-004-004": "Static regulation describes how well the output holds up against slow, long-term changes in load resistance, such as gradually adding equipment. It is the steady-state regulation figure. Short-term, rapid load changes are handled by dynamic regulation instead, so the long-term case is static regulation.",
"A-004-004-005": "Dynamic regulation describes how well the supply holds its output during short-term, rapid changes in load, such as the current bursts of an SSB or CW transmitter. It is the supply's response to quick load swings. Slow, long-term load changes are covered by static regulation, so the short-term case is dynamic regulation.",
"A-004-004-006": "Dynamic regulation depends on the supply's ability to deliver sudden bursts of current without sagging, and a larger output capacitor stores more charge to supply those bursts instantly. So increasing the output capacitor improves dynamic regulation. The choke or input capacitor do not directly stiffen the output against fast load changes the way the output capacitor does.",
"A-004-004-007": "An SSB or CW transmitter draws sudden current peaks, and a larger output capacitor stores extra charge to supply those peaks without the voltage dropping. So increasing the output capacitance gives better dynamic regulation. Reversing the electrolytic's polarity would simply destroy it, so that distractor is dangerous as well as wrong.",
"A-004-004-008": "Four diodes wired in a bridge conduct on alternate half-cycles so the load always sees the same polarity, which is the definition of rectification. So in this supply the bridge acts as a rectifier, converting AC into pulsating DC. It does not match impedance or tune anything; its only job there is rectifying.",
"A-004-004-009": "Fuses sit in the AC line before the transformer, where they carry alternating current, and a fuse can equally be placed in the DC output before the load. So the same component, the fuse, can be the one carrying AC at the input and DC near the output. Diodes and chokes do not serve both of those positions in this way.",
"A-004-004-010": "After the electrolytic filter capacitor smooths the rectified DC, that filtered output feeds the voltage regulator, which then holds the final output steady. So the capacitor's output connects to the voltage regulator. It does not feed a pi filter or a matching circuit in this regulated-supply chain.",
"A-004-004-011": "If the supply output ever rises above the regulator's input (for example when input power is removed while a charged capacitor holds the output up), the regulator can be damaged by reverse voltage. A diode across the input and output terminals harmlessly conducts in that situation, protecting the regulator from reverse voltages. Its job is reverse-voltage protection, not RF bypassing or added capacitance.",
"A-005-001-001": "A Hartley oscillator is identified by its inductive feedback: the resonant coil is tapped, and the tap point feeds part of the signal back to the input in phase, sustaining oscillation. Think of the H in Hartley standing for the coil (henrys). The capacitive divider belongs to the Colpitts, and link coupling or a neutralizing capacitor are unrelated to setting the feedback.",
"A-005-001-002": "A Colpitts oscillator uses a capacitive voltage divider (two series capacitors across the tank) to tap off the feedback signal, the capacitive counterpart of the Hartley's tapped coil. Remember Colpitts and capacitor both start with C. A tapped coil would make it a Hartley instead.",
"A-005-001-003": "A Pierce oscillator couples feedback through capacitance, with a quartz crystal acting as the high-Q resonant element for excellent stability. It is essentially a Colpitts arrangement built around a crystal, so the feedback path is capacitive. A tapped coil (Hartley) or neutralizing capacitor would not describe it.",
"A-005-001-004": "The Colpitts is favoured for a variable-frequency oscillator because its capacitive feedback gives good frequency stability over a tuning range. Stability is the prized trait in a VFO so the transmitted frequency does not drift. It is a free-running LC oscillator, not crystal-controlled, and oscillators are kept low-power buffered stages, so high output power is not the reason.",
"A-005-001-005": "In a PLL synthesizer the output frequency is locked to and multiplied from the reference, so any phase jitter in the reference is faithfully transferred and even magnified, appearing as phase noise on the output. This is why a clean, stable reference (often a crystal) is essential. The distractors confuse amplitude variation with phase, but a PLL locks on phase, not amplitude.",
"A-005-001-006": "Feedback taken from a capacitive divider (two series capacitors across the tank) is the defining feature of the Colpitts oscillator. A Hartley would use a tapped coil instead, and a Miller uses a different crystal arrangement. Match capacitive to Colpitts (both start with C).",
"A-005-001-007": "Silver mica capacitors are chosen for the feedback divider in a high-stability oscillator because they have very low loss, tight tolerance, and excellent temperature stability, so the frequency does not drift. Electrolytics are polarized, lossy, and only suit power supply filtering, while ceramic and Mylar drift more with temperature. Stability of the frequency-determining parts is everything in an oscillator.",
"A-005-001-008": "When feedback is obtained through a single capacitor in series with the crystal, the circuit is a Pierce oscillator, which relies on the crystal as its resonant element. The series capacitor lets you trim the exact operating frequency. A Colpitts uses two capacitors as a divider, and Hartley uses a tapped coil.",
"A-005-001-009": "An oscillator is the one circuit here that depends on positive (regenerative) feedback to sustain a continuous output, so a variable-frequency oscillator is correct. Mixers, detectors, and audio amplifiers process or amplify signals but do not require positive feedback to function. Positive feedback is the hallmark of any oscillator.",
"A-005-001-010": "An oscillator to set the frequency followed by a class C amplifier to boost power is the classic make-up of a simple two-stage CW (Morse) transmitter. Class C is highly efficient but non-linear, so it suits CW or FM but would distort SSB. There is no modulator or sideband generator described, ruling out the SSB and FM choices.",
"A-005-001-011": "Feedback through a single capacitor in series with the crystal identifies a Pierce oscillator, which uses the crystal directly as its frequency-controlling resonator. A Colpitts uses a two-capacitor divider, a Hartley a tapped coil, and a Franklin a two-stage design. The crystal-plus-series-capacitor signature points to Pierce.",
"A-005-002-001": "The adjustable pi network at a power amplifier output is an impedance-matching circuit: tuning it transforms the antenna impedance to the value the amplifier needs for maximum, efficient power transfer. It also helps filter harmonics, but its primary job is matching. It does not switch antennas or perform frequency multiplication.",
"A-005-002-002": "Returning the filament transformer secondary at its centre tap balances the AC heater supply so that 60 Hz hum is not impressed on the cathode and thus does not modulate the RF output. Without this balanced return the AC filament voltage would add unwanted hum to the emitted signal. The benefit is clean emission, not harmonic suppression or output power.",
"A-005-002-003": "In a grounded-grid triode amplifier the grid is at RF ground and the input signal is applied to the cathode, while output is taken from the plate. This configuration provides good stability and often needs no neutralization. Applying signal to the plate or grid would describe other configurations, not grounded grid.",
"A-005-002-004": "A blocking (coupling) capacitor connects the plate to the pi-network: it passes the RF output while blocking the high DC plate voltage from reaching the tuning network and antenna. A bypass capacitor would shunt RF to ground rather than couple it onward. So a DC-blocking capacitor is correct.",
"A-005-002-005": "The plate is fed its DC high voltage through an RF choke, and the far end of that choke connects to B+ (the high-voltage supply). The choke passes DC to the plate while blocking RF from entering the power supply. It is the high-voltage feed, not filament, ground, or bias.",
"A-005-002-006": "In a grounded-grid stage the cathode receives the input, and an RF choke in the cathode circuit returns to ground (B-), completing the DC path while keeping RF out of that return. The choke passes the cathode DC current to ground but blocks the RF signal. Hence the other end goes to B- / ground, not to B+ or the filament supply.",
"A-005-002-007": "A transformer secondary wired directly to the tube's heater pins supplies the low-voltage filament (heater) voltage that warms the cathode for electron emission. High voltage (B+) is fed through a choke to the plate, not directly from a transformer to the tube pins. So this transformer provides filament voltage.",
"A-005-002-008": "Efficiency = RF output power / DC input power, so DC input = output / efficiency = 400 W / 0.50 = 800 W. With plate current of 400 mA = 0.4 A, B+ = power / current = 800 / 0.4 = 2000 volts. Forgetting to divide by efficiency would wrongly give 1000 V.",
"A-005-002-009": "Each filament lead is grounded for RF through a bypass capacitor, which shunts any RF on the heater line to ground while leaving the DC/AC filament supply undisturbed. This keeps RF out of the filament wiring in a grounded-grid amplifier. They are bypass capacitors, not tuning, electrolytic, or blocking types.",
"A-005-002-010": "Before powering up after internal tuning, make certain all shielding is reinstalled and fastened: the shields protect you from lethal high voltage and RF burns and contain RF to prevent interference. Never bypass safety interlocks or run with shields off. Safety always comes first with high-power amplifiers.",
"A-005-002-011": "Harmonics created early in a transmitter are reduced later by tuned-circuit (resonant) coupling between stages, since each tuned circuit favours the desired frequency and rejects the unwanted harmonics. Bigger coupling capacitors pass more of everything, including harmonics, so they do not help. Selective tuned coupling is the filtering mechanism.",
"A-005-003-001": "Besides coupling energy from the oscillator to the class C amplifier, the RF transformer's winding works with capacitance to form a tuned (resonant) circuit, selecting the desired frequency. Inductive coupling alone transfers power, but its inductance also becomes part of a tuned circuit. It is not providing oscillator feedback here, which happens within the oscillator stage itself.",
"A-005-003-002": "An RF choke in series with grounded (bypass) capacitors forms a low-pass filter that feeds DC to the collector while keeping RF out of the power supply line. The choke passes DC but blocks RF, and the capacitors shunt any remaining RF to ground. This is a supply-decoupling low-pass arrangement, not a key-click or feedback circuit.",
"A-005-003-003": "In a two-stage CW transmitter the first stage is the oscillator and the second stage amplifies that signal to a usable level, so the second transistor acts as a power amplifier. The oscillator sets the frequency; the second stage simply boosts power. It is not a multiplier or oscillator in this simple design.",
"A-005-003-004": "Keying a buffer (or amplifier) stage rather than the oscillator itself keeps the oscillator running continuously, so it does not have to restart on each key-down and is far less likely to shift frequency (chirp). Letting the oscillator free-run gives a stable, clean note. The other options misstate the effect on clicks, bandwidth, and voltages.",
"A-005-003-005": "An amplifier is properly neutralized when changing or tuning the output (plate) circuit causes minimum change in grid current, showing no RF is feeding back from output to input. Residual feedback would make grid current jump as you tune the plate. So you adjust for the least change in grid current, not the least or most grid current itself.",
"A-005-003-006": "Neutralization deliberately feeds back a small out-of-phase signal that cancels the unwanted positive feedback caused by the tube's internal capacitance, preventing self-oscillation. In short, it cancels the effect of positive feedback. It has nothing to do with power-supply hum, grid modulation, or differential gain.",
"A-005-003-007": "The final amplifier is neutralized to eliminate parasitic (self-sustained) oscillations caused by internal feedback, which would otherwise generate spurious signals and instability. Cancelling that feedback keeps the stage a clean amplifier. Neutralization does not set modulation index, standby cutoff, or carrier frequency.",
"A-005-003-008": "Parasitic oscillations arise from accidental, unintended resonant frequencies formed by stray inductance and capacitance in the power amplifier, often well away from the operating frequency. These unplanned resonances let the stage self-oscillate. They are not the harmonics, drive level, or line mismatch of the operating signal.",
"A-005-003-009": "Parasitic oscillations occur mostly in RF power output stages, where high gain at RF plus stray reactances can create unintended resonant feedback loops. Audio output and rectifier stages do not operate at the RF frequencies where these spurious resonances form. High-gain RF power amplifiers are the usual offenders.",
"A-005-003-010": "Some vacuum tubes have enough interelectrode (plate-to-grid) capacitance to feed output back to the input and cause oscillation; neutralization cancels this feedback to stop it. The cure addresses the internal capacitance, not grid leakage, filament hum, or loaded Q. So neutralization fixes capacitance-driven oscillation.",
"A-005-003-011": "Parasitic oscillations in an RF power amplifier are commonly caused by lack of (or inadequate) neutralization, which lets internal feedback drive the stage into unwanted self-oscillation. Proper neutralization cancels that feedback. Overdrive, regulation, and harmonics are separate problems, not the typical cause of parasitics.",
"A-005-004-001": "A balanced modulator multiplies the audio and carrier in a way that cancels the carrier itself, leaving both sidebands, so its output is double-sideband suppressed carrier (DSB-SC). A following filter then removes one sideband to make SSB. By design it nulls the carrier, so full-carrier and single-sideband-direct answers are wrong.",
"A-005-004-002": "SSB is generated by the filter method: a balanced modulator produces a double-sideband suppressed-carrier signal, then a sharp filter removes one sideband, leaving a single sideband. The balanced modulator kills the carrier and the filter selects the wanted sideband. A reactance modulator produces FM, not SSB.",
"A-005-004-003": "The carrier is suppressed in the balanced modulator stage, where the carrier and audio combine so the carrier components cancel, leaving only the sidebands. The mechanical filter then removes one sideband but does not suppress the carrier. So carrier suppression happens in the balanced modulator.",
"A-005-004-004": "Compared with AM, SSB drops the carrier and one redundant sideband: removing the second sideband saves about 3 dB and removing the carrier about another 3 dB, for roughly a 6 dB advantage at the transmitter. At the receiver, SSB’s roughly half-as-wide bandwidth passes about half the noise, adding about a 3 dB advantage. This is the basis for the familiar figure that SSB is about 9 dB better than AM overall; the option claiming SSB needs more receiver bandwidth is wrong.",
"A-005-004-005": "In a two-tone test the two equal tones combine so the peak envelope power is twice the RF power of either tone alone, because at the peak the two equal voltages add and power goes as voltage squared. So PEP equals twice the power of one tone. Equal-to or one-half answers ignore this voltage addition at the envelope peak.",
"A-005-004-006": "Two audio sine waves (a two-tone test) are fed in so that the SSB output forms a clean crisscross envelope on a scope; any flattening or distortion of that pattern reveals non-linearity. A single tone produces a steady carrier-like output that cannot show linearity, and speech is too irregular to judge. Two tones are the standard.",
"A-005-004-007": "Two non-harmonically related audio tones are fed into the mic input and the transmitter output is viewed on an oscilloscope, where the envelope pattern reveals any flat-topping or distortion. They must be non-harmonic so their products do not overlap and mask distortion. A distortion analyzer is not how this visual envelope test is read.",
"A-005-004-008": "Any two tones may be used provided they fall within the transmitter's audio passband and are not harmonically related, so their intermodulation products are distinct and reveal distortion. Harmonically related tones would let products fall on top of each other and hide problems. There is no single required pair like 20 Hz/20 kHz.",
"A-005-004-009": "A two-tone test viewed on an oscilloscope measures the amplifier's linearity by showing whether the output envelope stays clean or distorts (flat-tops). It is an amplitude/distortion check on an SSB stage. Frequency deviation and modulation percentage apply to FM, not to an SSB linearity test.",
"A-005-004-010": "In a properly designed SSB transmitter the carrier is suppressed at least 40 dB below peak output, so almost none of the wasted carrier remains. A higher number means better suppression, and 40 dB is the accepted minimum standard. The no-more-than 20/30 dB answers describe inadequate suppression.",
"A-005-004-011": "Flat-topping is distortion caused by driving an SSB transmitter too hard, so the output envelope is clipped flat at the peaks and splatter is produced on adjacent frequencies. The cause is excessive drive, not too little current. Properly suppressed carrier or correctly adjusted ALC would prevent it, so those are not what flat-topping means.",
"A-005-005-001": "Modulation index for FM is the peak deviation divided by the modulating frequency: index = 3000 Hz / 1000 Hz = 3. Both quantities are in hertz so the result is a pure number. The answers 0.3 or 3000 come from dividing the wrong way or forgetting to divide.",
"A-005-005-002": "Modulation index = peak deviation / modulating frequency = 6 kHz / 2 kHz = 3. Keep both in the same units (kHz here) and the result is dimensionless. Reversing the ratio gives the wrong 0.333.",
"A-005-005-003": "Deviation ratio = maximum deviation / maximum modulating frequency = 5 kHz / 3 kHz = 1.66. Use the maximum swing (±5 kHz means 5 kHz) over the highest audio frequency. Inverting the ratio would wrongly give 0.6.",
"A-005-005-004": "Deviation ratio = maximum deviation / maximum modulating frequency = 7.5 kHz / 3.5 kHz = 2.14. Take the peak swing of 7.5 kHz over the top audio rate of 3.5 kHz. Reversing it gives the incorrect 0.47.",
"A-005-005-005": "With no modulation the FM carrier sits at its resting frequency, called the centre (rest) frequency, and modulation makes it swing above and below this point. Deviation and frequency shift describe the swing away from centre, not the unmodulated value. So the unmodulated carrier frequency is the centre frequency.",
"A-005-005-006": "In FM the amount of deviation depends solely on the amplitude (loudness) of the modulating signal, not its frequency: louder audio pushes the carrier farther from centre. The modulating frequency instead determines how fast the carrier swings, not how far. So amplitude alone sets the deviation.",
"A-005-005-007": "Frequency modulation with a single tone theoretically produces an infinite number of sideband pairs (described by Bessel functions), though only those with significant amplitude matter in practice. This is unlike AM, which makes just one pair per tone. So the correct count is infinite, not two or four.",
"A-005-005-008": "One type of deviation meter increases modulation until a Bessel carrier null occurs, then computes deviation by multiplying the modulating frequency by the known modulation index at that null. The carrier disappears at specific index values, giving a precise calibration point. The other options misdescribe this null-based method.",
"A-005-005-009": "Because the carrier-null method computes deviation as modulating frequency times modulation index, you must know the modulating frequency you are feeding in to use such a meter. The index value is fixed by which null you observe, so the unknown you supply is the modulating frequency. The IF filter passband is not what you need to know.",
"A-005-005-010": "Carson's rule gives the significant bandwidth as 2 × (peak deviation + modulating frequency) = 2 × (5 kHz + 3 kHz) = 2 × 8 = 16 kHz. Add deviation and audio frequency first, then double. Forgetting to double or to add the audio gives the smaller wrong answers.",
"A-005-005-011": "The reactance modulator runs at 12.21 MHz but the final output is 146.52 MHz, a multiplication factor of 146.52 / 12.21 = 12. Frequency multiplication multiplies deviation by the same factor, so the oscillator's deviation must be the final ±5 kHz divided by 12 = ±416.7 Hz. So the low-frequency stage deviates only ±416.7 Hz.",
"A-005-006-001": "When two transmitters' signals mix in a non-linear final amplifier and produce radiated sum and difference frequencies, this is intermodulation interference. The mixing creates new spurious frequencies not present in either original signal. It is not simple adjacent-channel interference or desensitization, which are different effects.",
"A-005-006-002": "Intermodulation typically happens when two repeaters are physically close, so each transmitter's signal enters the other's final amplifier and the non-linear stage mixes them into new sum and difference products. Proximity plus a non-linear amplifier is the recipe. Aircraft reflections and feedback are not the usual mechanism.",
"A-005-006-003": "A terminated circulator or ferrite isolator in the transmission line passes the transmitter's outgoing power but absorbs signals coming back in, so the other transmitter's signal cannot reach the final amplifier and mix. This blocks the reverse path that causes intermod. Simple high- or low-pass filters do not stop on-band signals from a nearby transmitter on the same band.",
"A-005-006-004": "Third-order intermod products fall at 2f1 - f2 and 2f2 - f1. Using 146.52 and the unknown x with the receiver at 146.70: 2 × 146.52 - x = 146.70 gives x = 146.34 MHz, and 2x - 146.52 = 146.70 gives x = 146.61 MHz. So the two likely interfering frequencies are 146.34 MHz and 146.61 MHz.",
"A-005-006-005": "A phase modulator varies the tuning (reactance) of an amplifier's tank circuit to shift the signal's phase, which produces FM (indirect FM). Changing the tank reactance changes the instantaneous frequency. A balanced modulator or mixer would not create FM this way.",
"A-005-006-006": "A pre-emphasis network is added at the FM transmitter to boost the higher audio frequencies relative to the lower ones before modulation, which improves the high-frequency signal-to-noise ratio. The receiver then applies the opposite de-emphasis to restore natural balance and cut high-frequency noise. De-emphasis is the receiver-side complement, so the transmitter network is pre-emphasis.",
"A-005-006-007": "A 2-metre repeater duplexer needs cavity filters: high-Q resonant cavities provide the very sharp, low-loss selectivity required to let transmit and receive share one antenna without the transmitter swamping the receiver. L-C, crystal, and DSP filters cannot give that combination of low loss and steep skirts at VHF power levels. Cavities are the standard choice.",
"A-005-006-008": "Phase modulation and direct frequency modulation differ in how deviation varies with audio frequency, and the practical difference shows up as pre-emphasis: phase modulation inherently emphasizes higher audio frequencies, equivalent to the pre-emphasis applied to true FM. So pre-emphasis characterizes the distinction. Centre frequency and inversion are unrelated.",
"A-005-006-009": "A compressor and clipper are placed between the audio amplifier and the modulator so the audio is level-controlled and peak-limited before it modulates the carrier, improving talk power and preventing overdeviation. They must act on the audio signal path ahead of modulation. Placing them after the modulator or oscillator would be too late.",
"A-005-006-010": "For an FM transmitter the three key parameters to verify are power output, frequency deviation, and frequency stability, ensuring it is on frequency, not overdeviating, and at legal power. These directly affect signal quality and interference. Carrier suppression and sideband power are SSB/AM concerns, not FM.",
"A-005-006-011": "Intermodulation products come from non-linear mixing in stages handling multiple strong signals, the final amplifier, the receiver front end, or passive junctions (passive intermod). The intermediate-frequency stage handles a single converted signal and is not where intermod typically originates. So the IF stage is the odd one out.",
"A-005-007-001": "Automatic level control (ALC) holds the peak RF output of an SSB transmitter roughly constant by reducing gain when input peaks rise, preventing overdrive and flat-topping. It acts on the transmit chain. AGC, AOC, and AVC are receiver gain-control terms, not the transmit peak-limiting circuit.",
"A-005-007-002": "Speech compression amplifies weak (low-level) speech fully while reducing or limiting amplification of strong (high-level) peaks, which raises average power and improves intelligibility without overdriving. The first option states this correctly. Compression actually improves the effective signal-to-noise of speech rather than lowering it.",
"A-005-007-003": "A digital signal processor contains an analog-to-digital converter, a mathematical transform, and a digital-to-analog converter, but there is no such thing as an aliasing amplifier; aliasing is an unwanted artifact to be avoided, not a circuit block. So the aliasing amplifier is the item that does not belong. The other three are genuine DSP components.",
"A-005-007-004": "The number of discrete levels is 2 raised to the number of bits, so for 256 levels you need n where 2ⁿ = 256, and 2⁸ = 256, giving 8 bits. Each added bit doubles the levels. 4 bits gives only 16 and 6 bits only 64, both too few.",
"A-005-007-005": "Each added bit doubles the resolution, and doubling corresponds to about 6 dB (since 20 × log₁₀(2) ≈ 6 dB), so one more bit adds roughly 6 dB of dynamic range. This is the well-known 6 dB-per-bit rule for digitizers. The 1, 3, and 4 dB answers do not match the factor-of-two-per-bit relationship.",
"A-005-007-006": "A circuit using an analog-to-digital converter, a mathematical transform, a digital-to-analog converter, and a low-pass (reconstruction) filter is a digital signal processor (DSP). These blocks digitize, process, and reconstruct the signal. The other names are not standard terms for this complete chain.",
"A-005-007-007": "Frequency division is a digital/logic technique, not an analog signal-processing method, so it is the one not associated with analog processing. Compression, bandwidth limiting, and clipping all operate directly on analog waveforms. Hence frequency division is the odd one out.",
"A-005-007-008": "Peak limiting in a speech processor is done by compression, AF (audio) clipping, or RF clipping, but there is no method called frequency clipping. Clipping flattens peaks in either the audio or RF domain, and compression rides the gain down on peaks. So frequency clipping is the non-existent method.",
"A-005-007-009": "Clipping the audio waveform flattens its peaks, and those sharp corners are rich in harmonics, so AF clipping increases harmonic distortion that can fall outside the desired passband. That distortion is the main drawback. RF clipping followed by filtering reduces this problem, which is why RF clipping is generally preferred.",
"A-005-007-010": "Compared with AF clipping, RF clipping is harder and more expensive to implement, but it produces less distortion because the resulting splatter can be filtered out at RF. The statement that it is easier to implement is therefore the incorrect description. Its advantage is lower distortion, not lower cost or complexity.",
"A-005-007-011": "Automatic Level Control is essentially a form of RF compression: it reduces the transmitter's gain on RF peaks to hold output level constant and prevent overdrive. It acts on the RF/output level, not on the audio or by clipping. So ALC is another name for RF compression.",
"A-005-008-001": "Varicode uses code elements of unequal length, assigning shorter codes to common characters and longer codes to rare ones (similar in spirit to Morse), which is why it is used in PSK31. Baudot and ASCII use fixed-length codes, and AX.25 is a packet protocol, not a variable-length character code. So Varicode is the variable-length code.",
"A-005-008-002": "The base (lowest) layer of the OSI model is the physical layer, which covers the actual electrical/mechanical connection, here the TNC-to-terminal interconnection. Higher layers (link, network, transport) handle framing, routing, and end-to-end delivery. So the physical interconnection corresponds to the physical layer.",
"A-005-008-003": "A Cyclic Redundancy Check appends a calculated value so the receiver can recompute it and detect whether the data was corrupted; its purpose is error detection. It flags bad frames but does not by itself correct them. CRC is not a compression method, so the compression answers are wrong.",
"A-005-008-004": "ASCII's advantage over Baudot is its larger character set that includes both upper- and lower-case letters (plus more symbols), whereas 5-bit Baudot cannot. ASCII has no built-in error correction and uses more, not fewer, bits per character. So the upper/lower-case capability is the real advantage.",
"A-005-008-005": "AMTOR ARQ (Mode A) is an automatic-repeat-request system: the receiving station detects errors and automatically requests retransmission of any bad characters. This handshaking gives reliable copy on a clear path between two stations. The other options describe FEC, packet FCS, or claim no error control, none of which match Mode A.",
"A-005-008-006": "AMTOR FEC (Mode B) is forward error correction used for broadcasts, where each character is sent twice (time-diversity) so the receiver can recover it without a return channel. There is no acknowledgement path in FEC mode, unlike ARQ. So sending each character twice is the FEC method.",
"A-005-008-007": "APRS supports two-way messaging, telemetry, and local information broadcasts, but it does not provide automatic link establishment (ALE), which is a separate HF technology for selecting usable frequencies. So automatic link establishment is the function APRS lacks. The other three are core APRS features.",
"A-005-008-008": "A CRC is generated using a hash-type function (polynomial division) that condenses the message into a short check value. Huffman coding, convolution codes, and Lempel-Ziv are compression or error-correction techniques, not CRC generators. So a hash function is the algorithm behind a CRC.",
"A-005-008-009": "AX.25 is the link-layer protocol used for amateur packet radio, defining how frames are addressed and exchanged. It is specifically the packet mode standard. RTTY, ASCII, and spread spectrum are unrelated modes, so packet is the correct association.",
"A-005-008-010": "Baudot uses 5 information bits per character, giving 32 possible codes, which it extends with letters/figures shift to cover the full set. ASCII uses 7 and its extensions 8 bits. So Baudot's information-bit count is 5.",
"A-005-008-011": "Standard ASCII uses 7 bits, and the ISO-8859 extension adds one more to make 8 information bits, doubling the character set to include accented and special characters. So ISO-8859 uses 8 bits. The 5-, 6-, and 7-bit answers describe Baudot or plain ASCII, not the extension.",
"A-005-009-001": "Spread spectrum is the wideband technique in which the RF carrier is deliberately varied over a wide bandwidth according to a predetermined (pseudo-random) sequence known to both ends. Spreading the energy gives interference resistance and low detectability. The other terms describe unrelated modes, not this carrier-spreading scheme.",
"A-005-009-002": "Frequency hopping is the spread-spectrum method where the carrier's centre frequency jumps among many channels many times per second following a pseudo-random list shared by transmitter and receiver. The carrier moves; it is not phase-shifted as in direct sequence. So changing channels per a pseudo-random list is frequency hopping.",
"A-005-009-003": "Direct sequence spread spectrum uses a very fast pseudo-random binary bit stream to phase-shift (modulate) the RF carrier, spreading its energy across a wide band. The fast code, not channel hopping, does the spreading here. So the phase-shifting-by-fast-bitstream description is direct sequence.",
"A-005-009-004": "Frequency hopping is a technique of spread spectrum transmission, where the carrier jumps among channels in a pseudo-random pattern. It is not part of AMTOR, packet, or RTTY, which are conventional narrowband modes. So frequency hopping belongs to spread spectrum.",
"A-005-009-005": "Direct sequence is one of the spread spectrum methods, using a fast pseudo-random code to phase-modulate and spread the carrier. AMTOR, packet, and RTTY are narrowband digital modes, not spread spectrum. So direct sequence goes with spread spectrum.",
"A-005-009-006": "Spread spectrum alters the carrier using a pseudo-random sequence that both transmitter and receiver know, so the receiver can despread and recover the signal. True random noise could not be reproduced at the receiver, so it cannot be used. The sequence must be pseudo-random (deterministic yet noise-like).",
"A-005-009-007": "A spread-spectrum signal is hard to monitor because your receiver must be frequency- (and code-) synchronized to the transmitter's pseudo-random sequence to despread it; without that key the energy just looks like noise. The signal is wider than normal, not narrower, so that distractor is wrong. Synchronization to the spreading code is the barrier.",
"A-005-009-008": "In frequency-hopping spread spectrum the carrier frequency is changed (hopped) among many channels following a pseudo-random list shared by both stations. The carrier moves in frequency rather than being amplitude- or phase-modulated to spread it. So the pseudo-random channel-changing description is correct.",
"A-005-009-009": "In direct-sequence spread spectrum the carrier is phase-shifted by a fast pseudo-random binary bit stream, which spreads its energy across a wide band. The spreading comes from rapid phase modulation, not from hopping channels or amplitude/frequency companding. So the phase-shift-by-bitstream answer is correct.",
"A-005-009-010": "Spread-spectrum reception is interference-resistant because the receiver despreads only signals that follow the correct spreading code; any signal not using that algorithm is spread out and suppressed during despreading, while the wanted signal is collapsed back to full strength. It is not about high power or special DSP filters. The matched-code processing is what rejects interference.",
"A-005-009-011": "Frequency hopping works by changing the RF carrier frequency very rapidly according to a particular pseudo-random sequence known to both transmitter and receiver. The receiver hops in step to follow the signal. It does not rely on detecting interference and signalling the transmitter, which describes a different, adaptive scheme.",
"A-006-001-001": "Converting every incoming signal down to one fixed intermediate frequency (IF) lets the designer build the high-gain, sharply tuned IF filters once and optimize them perfectly, instead of trying to make tuned circuits track sharply across the whole tuning range. That fixed IF is where the selectivity comes from. The distractors mix in unrelated functions like squelch, detection or limiting that are not what the frequency-conversion step provides.",
"A-006-001-002": "Picking the IF is mostly about keeping unwanted responses out: the image frequency sits 2×IF away from the wanted signal, so a higher IF pushes the image far enough that the front-end can reject it, while still being low enough for good IF selectivity. So image rejection and other spurious responses dominate the choice. Noise figure, cross-modulation and interference to others are set by different parts of the receiver, not by the IF value.",
"A-006-001-003": "In double conversion the first IF is made high so the image frequency lands far away and is easily filtered, then a second conversion drops to a low IF for sharp selectivity. This gives much better image rejection for the same front-end tuned-circuit quality than single conversion can. The other options (stability, sensitivity, loudness) are not what the extra conversion buys you.",
"A-006-001-004": "A crystal filter provides the narrow, sharp-skirted selectivity a communications receiver needs, and that selectivity is set at the fixed intermediate frequency, so the crystal filter lives in the IF circuits. Crystals are cut for one frequency, which is why they suit the fixed IF and not the tunable local oscillator. The detector and audio stages handle the signal after selectivity has already been established.",
"A-006-001-005": "Each extra oscillator and mixer in a multiple-conversion design creates more sum-and-difference products, and any of those mixing combinations can let an unwanted signal sneak through as a spurious response. More frequencies being multiplied together means more chances for spurs. The problem is the added mixing products, not poorer IF selectivity, higher sensitivity, or AGC overload.",
"A-006-001-006": "The first conversion uses a high IF so the image frequency is far off and easy to reject, giving image rejection; the second conversion drops to a low IF where narrow filters give the fine selectivity. So the order is image rejection first, then selectivity. The reversed answer (selectivity then image rejection) is the tempting trap because both words are correct but the sequence is backwards.",
"A-006-001-007": "The RF amplifier is the stage that handles the actual received signal, so both its input and output tuned circuits are peaked at the incoming frequency to amplify it while rejecting off-channel signals. The local oscillator runs at a different frequency (offset by the IF), and the detector and audio stages work at the IF or audio, not the received frequency.",
"A-006-001-008": "The mixer takes the tunable input (RF/preselector following the variable local oscillator) on one side and feeds the fixed-tuned IF amplifier on the other, so it sits between a tunable stage and a fixed-tuned stage. That is exactly the mixer's job, to translate the variable input frequency to the fixed IF. The RF amp is before the mixer, the IF amp after it, and the local oscillator is the tunable source, not the in-between stage.",
"A-006-001-009": "The mixer produces sum and difference frequencies, so the received signal is either LO − IF or LO + IF. Here 16 MHz − 9 MHz = 7 MHz (the low-side answer); the high-side image would be 16 + 9 = 25 MHz. Of the choices given, 7 MHz is the frequency the receiver is tuned to.",
"A-006-001-010": "Double conversion means two mixing steps, so there are two IF stages and two local oscillators, one for each conversion. The beat-frequency oscillator is a separate, additional oscillator used only to recover SSB, so it is mentioned on top of those two. Counting only one IF/one LO ignores the second conversion, and three local oscillators wrongly counts the BFO as a conversion oscillator.",
"A-006-001-011": "Making the first IF high in a double-conversion receiver moves the image frequency far from the wanted signal, so a simple front end can reject it, giving less image interference for the same front-end selectivity. The extra conversion is about image rejection, not curing drift, boosting sensitivity, or making the audio louder.",
"A-006-002-001": "The mixer beats the incoming RF signal against the local oscillator and outputs the difference (the intermediate frequency), so the signal can then be handled by the fixed IF amplifiers. Changing the incoming frequency to the IF is the mixer's whole purpose. It does not remove images, allow multiple IFs, or make audio; those happen elsewhere.",
"A-006-002-002": "SSB transmits only one sideband with the carrier suppressed, and the detector needs that carrier to recover the audio, so the BFO reinjects a locally generated carrier to take its place. Without it the SSB signal demodulates as unintelligible. The BFO does not phase out a sideband, narrow the IF, or create a missing sideband; it simply supplies the missing carrier reference.",
"A-006-002-003": "Mixing the incoming signal with the local oscillator produces sum and difference products, and the receiver uses the difference, which is the fixed intermediate frequency. That IF is what the following selective amplifier stages are tuned to. It is not an audio frequency (that comes after detection) nor just a generic RF.",
"A-006-002-004": "The LO sits one IF away from the signal, so LO = signal ± IF. With signal 3600 kHz and IF 9 MHz = 9000 kHz: 3600 + 9000 = 12 600 kHz (high-side) or 9000 − 3600 = 5400 kHz (low-side). Of the listed choices, 5400 kHz is correct; note 21 600 kHz comes from wrongly adding 3600 to 18 000.",
"A-006-002-005": "For CW and SSB the detector needs a tone, so the BFO is offset by a few hundred hertz to a couple of kilohertz; beating the offset BFO against the incoming signal produces an audible difference tone (the 500–1500 Hz beat note). Without that offset there would be zero-beat and no audible tone. It is not there to amplify or protect the signal.",
"A-006-002-006": "Receiver oscillators must be stable so the tuning does not drift off the signal, and spectrally pure so they do not generate extra frequencies that create spurious responses or reciprocal mixing. Sensitivity and selectivity are properties of amplifier and filter stages, not of the oscillators themselves, so those options confuse oscillator requirements with receiver performance terms.",
"A-006-002-007": "The variable capacitor with its trimmer and inductor forms the resonant circuit that sets the oscillator frequency, and since the LO must tune across the band to keep the difference at the fixed IF, this is the local-oscillator tuning. The BFO runs near the fixed IF and does not tune across the band, so the answers naming the BFO are wrong.",
"A-006-002-008": "Without an RF amplifier the variable capacitor and inductor at the mixer input form the preselector tuned circuit, peaked at the wanted reception frequency to keep images and off-channel signals out of the mixer. That is the preselector tuning the receiver to the reception frequency. The BFO and LO are separate oscillators, not this input resonant circuit.",
"A-006-002-009": "The stage that combines an incoming signal with an oscillator to produce a different output frequency is the mixer: 14.25 MHz − 13.795 MHz = 0.455 MHz = 455 kHz, exactly the IF. A BFO works at the IF for detection, a VFO is just an oscillator, and a multiplier raises a frequency by a whole number, so only the mixer does this frequency translation.",
"A-006-002-010": "Before mixing, the RF amplifier and the first mixer both have input tuned circuits peaked at the wanted received frequency so they pass the same signal. The local oscillator is deliberately offset by the IF, and the IF amplifier works at the fixed IF, so those stages are tuned to different frequencies, not the received one.",
"A-006-002-011": "The mixer's intended job is to combine the incoming signal with the local oscillator and output the intermediate frequency for the IF stages. Spurious signals are an unwanted side effect of mixing, not its purpose, so 'produces spurious signals' is the trap; the mixer is not a buffer and does not by itself demodulate SSB.",
"A-006-003-001": "The noise floor is the level of the receiver's own internally generated noise, so the weakest signal you can actually detect is one that just rises above that noise. A signal buried below the noise floor cannot be distinguished. It is about internal receiver noise, not atmospheric conditions, RF overload, or just the local oscillator's noise alone.",
"A-006-003-002": "The first IF amplifier provides much of the receiver's gain and is where the selective filtering lives, so its purpose is to improve both selectivity and gain. Noise figure is set mainly by the RF/front-end stages, not the IF, and the IF does not tune out cross-modulation, so those options misplace functions that belong elsewhere.",
"A-006-003-003": "The RF amplifier should have just enough gain to lift weak signals above the noise the first mixer generates, because the mixer is a relatively noisy stage. Too little gain leaves signals below mixer noise; too much gain (the tempting 'as much as possible' answer) overloads the mixer and hurts dynamic range. So the goal is enough gain to overcome mixer noise, no more.",
"A-006-003-004": "The RF amplifier's main value is that it amplifies the signal before the noisy mixer, setting a low overall noise figure and thus good sensitivity. Most of the receiver's gain actually comes from the IF stages, not the RF amp, so 'provide most of the gain' is the tempting but wrong choice; the RF amp's real payoff is noise figure.",
"A-006-003-005": "UHF FM receiver sensitivity is commonly quoted as the RF input level needed to reach 12 dB SINAD, a standard measure of when the recovered audio is sufficiently above noise and distortion. BER is used for digital modes, noise figure and gain are different specs, so 12 dB SINAD is the conventional FM sensitivity figure.",
"A-006-003-006": "Dynamic range is the decibel span between the strongest signal the receiver can handle without producing audible distortion and the weakest detectable signal (its sensitivity). It captures how wide a range of signal strengths the receiver copes with at once. Stability, noise figure and 'design parameter' describe other properties, not this ratio.",
"A-006-003-007": "Noise figure measures how much noise the receiver adds, so a lower noise figure means weaker signals stay above the noise and can be heard, which is greater sensitivity. Selectivity and rejection are set by filters, and stability by oscillators, so only sensitivity tracks the noise figure.",
"A-006-003-008": "Noise contributes most where the signal is still weak and being amplified at the front, so in a good design the dominant internal noise comes from the RF amplifier and the mixer. By the time the signal reaches the detector and audio stages it is already strong, so noise added there matters far less.",
"A-006-003-009": "On HF the external noise picked up by the antenna, both natural (atmospheric) and man-made, is far larger than the receiver's own internal noise, so a very low noise figure brings no benefit, the external noise dominates anyway. This is why ultra-low-noise front ends matter at VHF/UHF but not on HF. The other options misattribute the cause to ionospheric effects, modulation type, or later stages.",
"A-006-003-010": "Dynamic range is specifically the span of signal amplitudes, from the weakest detectable to the strongest tolerable, that the receiver can handle simultaneously. AGC and noise figure relate to gain control and sensitivity rather than this amplitude span, so dynamic range is the correct term for accommodating multiple signal levels.",
"A-006-003-011": "The resonant tuned circuits before and after the RF stage, which select the wanted frequency and reject images and off-channel signals, are together called the preselector. They pre-select the band of interest ahead of the mixer. Preamplifier refers only to a gain stage, and preamble/pass-selector are not real receiver terms.",
"A-006-004-001": "FM transmitters boost (pre-emphasize) the higher audio frequencies before transmission, so the receiver must apply the opposite, a de-emphasis network, to attenuate the highs and restore the original balance, which proportionally brings the lower frequencies back up. Pre-emphasis is what the transmitter does; using it again at the receiver would double the distortion instead of correcting it.",
"A-006-004-002": "A product detector recovers SSB and CW by mixing the incoming IF signal with a locally generated carrier (from the BFO), producing the difference as audio. It is essentially a mixer used for detection. It does not provide oscillations to a mixer, narrow bandpass, or detect cross-modulation; its defining action is multiplying signal by a local carrier.",
"A-006-004-003": "If only strong signals are distorted while weak ones are clean, the problem is the gain-riding circuit that responds to strong signals, namely the AGC, being defective or misadjusted. A fault in the IF, AF or RF amplifier itself would typically distort signals regardless of strength, so the strength-dependent symptom points specifically at the AGC.",
"A-006-004-004": "AGC keeps the audio level roughly constant by sensing signal strength and reducing receiver gain as the signal gets stronger (and raising gain on weak signals). So a stronger signal causes the AGC to reduce gain. Increasing gain would do the opposite of its purpose, and AGC is meant to prevent distortion and limiting, not cause them.",
"A-006-004-005": "After the IF amplifier raises the signal to a usable level, that amplified IF is fed to the detector, which recovers the audio (or other modulation). The RF amplifier and LO come before the IF, and the audio output stage comes after detection, so the detector is the correct next stage.",
"A-006-004-006": "The detector recovers a low-level audio signal that is too weak to drive a speaker, so it is sent to the AF (audio) amplifier for amplification first. Feeding it directly to the speaker would be far too quiet, and it is certainly not grounded or sent back to the RF amplifier.",
"A-006-004-007": "Besides manual volume controls, a receiver holds its output roughly steady automatically with automatic gain control, which adjusts gain to compensate for varying signal strength. Automatic frequency control corrects tuning, not level, and 'inverse gain control' and 'automatic load control' are not the standard receiver output-leveling circuit.",
"A-006-004-008": "AGC works by varying the gain of the early high-gain stages, so the control voltage is fed back to the RF and IF amplifiers where it can throttle gain before the signal grows too large. Applying it to the audio stages would act too late, after detection, so the RF and IF amplifiers are the correct targets.",
"A-006-004-009": "AGC control voltage can be developed either from the IF signal level (IF derived) or from the recovered audio (audio derived), the two standard methods. The other combinations mix in RF- or detector-derived labels that are not the conventional pair, so IF derived or audio derived is correct.",
"A-006-004-010": "An AGC loop is characterized mainly by its threshold (the signal level at which gain reduction begins) and its decay time (how quickly gain recovers after the signal drops). Together these set how the loop responds. Blanking, slope, bandwidth, clipping and hang time describe other circuits, not the basic AGC behaviour.",
"A-006-004-011": "Combining the IF signal with a beat-frequency oscillator to produce audio is exactly what a product detector does, multiplying the two to yield the difference as audio for SSB or CW. AGC controls gain, a VFO is an oscillator, and a power supply provides power, so only the product detector performs this detection.",
"A-006-005-001": "Image rejection depends on filtering out the image frequency before it reaches the mixer, and that selectivity ahead of the mixer is provided by the RF amplifier and preselector. So the front-end preselector sets the image rejection ratio. The IF filter, product detector and AGC act after or apart from the mixing step and cannot remove an image once it has been converted to the IF.",
"A-006-005-002": "Desensitization is the loss of receiver sensitivity when a strong nearby signal drives the front end toward overload, reducing gain available for the wanted weak signal. The strong signal need not be on your frequency, just near it. Cross-modulation transfers modulation between signals and squelch/quieting are different effects, so desensitization is the correct term.",
"A-006-005-003": "Desensitization is caused by strong signals near the received frequency overloading the front end and robbing gain from the wanted signal. Squelch and audio gain settings only affect how much audio you hear; they do not reduce the receiver's RF sensitivity, so the strong nearby signal is the real cause.",
"A-006-005-004": "Adding a cavity (or other sharp filter) ahead of the receiver attenuates the strong off-frequency signal before it can overload the front end, reducing desensitization. Lowering squelch gain or raising bandwidth does not stop the overload, and transmitter audio gain is unrelated, so the cavity filter is the effective fix.",
"A-006-005-005": "Intermodulation arises when two or more signals mix in a nonlinear circuit or device, producing new sum-and-difference products that fall on other frequencies. A perfectly linear stage would not create these products. Too little gain, positive feedback or lack of neutralization cause other problems, so nonlinearity is the root cause of intermod.",
"A-006-005-006": "The image frequency sits 2×IF away from the wanted signal, so using a very high (VHF) IF moves the image far outside the front-end filter passband where it is easily rejected. A higher IF does not widen tuning range or tune out cross-modulation; its key benefit is pushing the image far from the passband.",
"A-006-005-007": "Intermodulation interference is produced when two or more strong signals mix together in the nonlinear front end of the receiver, generating spurious products that land on the wanted frequency. The defining cause is signals mixing in the front end. It is not specifically about transmitter final stages or only the IF amplifiers, where the wanted signal has already been filtered.",
"A-006-005-008": "Instability (drift and unwanted oscillation) comes from things that physically change the tuned circuits, such as temperature variations, mechanical movement, and stray feedback. The accuracy of the dial display only affects how correctly the frequency is shown, not whether the receiver actually stays put, so it is NOT a cause of instability.",
"A-006-005-009": "Frequency stability depends on the oscillators, and the local oscillator (plus the power supply that feeds it) is where drift usually starts, since small voltage or temperature changes shift its frequency and therefore the tuning. The detector, RF amplifier and mixer do not set the tuned frequency, so they are not the usual source of drift.",
"A-006-005-010": "When a strong signal hits a receiver with poor dynamic range, the overloaded nonlinear front end causes desensitization, intermodulation, and cross-modulation. Feedback, by contrast, is a circuit-design or stability issue, not a direct result of a strong signal overloading the front end, so it is the odd one out.",
"A-006-005-011": "In a crowded band the limiting factor is how the receiver handles strong nearby signals, and the two-tone third-order IMD dynamic range with a realistic spacing (here 10 MHz) directly measures resistance to intermodulation from strong out-of-band signals. The third-order intercept point and blocking range are related single specs, but the two-tone IMD dynamic range is the practical performance indicator, while IF rejection ratio addresses a different problem.",
"A-007-001-001": "A \"Transformer\"-type tuner uses a tapped inductor (an autotransformer), not a Pi network, so calling it a Pi-type tuner is the FALSE statement. The other three statements are all true of a transformer tuner: it accepts a 50 Ω input and can match a wide range of low-to-high output impedances. Watch the wording — the question asks which statement is false, so the correct choice is the one that misidentifies the circuit.",
"A-007-001-002": "A \"Series\"-type tuner places a series reactance in the line; it is not a Pi network, so the false statement is the one calling it a Pi-type tuner. The other statements correctly describe a series tuner: 50 Ω input and the ability to match low-to-high impedances. The trap is that all options sound plausible, but only the wrong circuit name is false.",
"A-007-001-003": "An L-network tuner is named for its L shape (a series element and a shunt element); the false statement here is the claim that the antenna output is always high impedance. An L-network can match either up or down depending on which side the shunt element is on, and it does suit a vertical ground-plane and a 50 Ω input. So the misleading absolute \"high impedance\" output is the incorrect description.",
"A-007-001-004": "A Pi tuner is built from two shunt capacitors and a series inductor in a π shape, so it is not a series-type tuner — that is the false statement. The genuine facts are that it has a 50 Ω input, matches low-to-high impedances, and is correctly called a Pi-type circuit. The distractor mislabels the network as a series type.",
"A-007-001-005": "A pi-network is named for its π shape and consists of one inductor and two capacitors (or two inductors and one capacitor), giving the series-shunt arrangement that transforms impedance. The four-reactor and \"isolated from ground\" answers describe other circuits, and \"power incidence network\" is meaningless. The defining feature is the three-element L-C topology shaped like the Greek letter π.",
"A-007-001-006": "Of the choices, the Pi-network offers the greatest impedance transformation (matching) ratio because its two adjustable capacitors plus inductor give a wide tuning range. Chebyshev and Butterworth are filter response types, not matching topologies, and an L-network has a fixed, limited ratio set by the two impedances. So the Pi-network wins on transformation range.",
"A-007-001-007": "An L-network has only two components, so once you pick the two impedances to match, the component values (and Q) are fixed — it can match only one specific impedance transformation, giving it a small matching range. It is not limited by thermal stability, self-resonance, or power handling. Adding a third element (as in a Pi or T) restores adjustability and range.",
"A-007-001-008": "A matching network transforms impedance by using reactive elements to cancel the load's reactance and to scale the resistive part up or down to the desired value. It does not create negative resistance or transconductance, and it does not literally substitute its own resistance for the load. The key idea is reactance cancellation plus resistance transformation, done with lossless L and C.",
"A-007-001-009": "A pi-L network adds a second L-section after the pi-section, and the extra low-pass stage gives greater harmonic suppression than a plain pi-network. Both can match a multiband antenna, but the pi-L's added filtering keeps harmonics out of the antenna better. So the advantage is harmonic suppression, not efficiency or transformation range.",
"A-007-001-010": "The Pi-L network provides the greatest harmonic suppression because it is effectively a pi-section followed by an additional L-section, adding an extra low-pass pole. A plain pi-network and an L-network roll off harmonics less steeply, and an \"inverse pi-network\" is not the standard high-suppression choice. More cascaded low-pass stages mean steeper attenuation of harmonics.",
"A-007-001-011": "A Smith Chart is a graphical tool that lets you solve transmission-line and impedance-matching problems by reading points and moving along circles, simplifying otherwise messy complex-number math. It is not limited to those problems only, and it is not for DC circuits. Its real value is replacing calculation with a visual construction on the complex reflection-coefficient plane.",
"A-007-002-001": "A quarter-wave line acts as an impedance inverter: it transforms the far-end impedance to its inverse referred to the line's characteristic impedance (Zin = Z0² / Zload). With the far end shorted (Zload = 0), the source sees a very high impedance. This is why a shorted quarter-wave stub behaves like a parallel-resonant (open) circuit at that frequency.",
"A-007-002-002": "Because a quarter-wave line inverts impedance (Zin = Z0² / Zload), an open far end (Zload = infinity) is transformed into a very low impedance at the source. So an open quarter-wave stub looks like a short circuit. This is the mirror image of the shorted quarter-wave case, which looks open.",
"A-007-002-003": "A half-wave line repeats the far-end impedance exactly back to the source (Zin = Zload), since it is two quarter-wave inversions in series that cancel. An open far end therefore presents a very high impedance at the source. The half-wave \"repeater\" property is why an open half-wave line still looks open.",
"A-007-002-004": "A half-wave line reflects the load impedance straight through unchanged (Zin = Zload), because two successive quarter-wave inversions cancel. With the far end shorted, the source sees a very low impedance — a short still looks like a short. This repeating behaviour is the defining trait of a half-wavelength line.",
"A-007-002-005": "Velocity factor is the speed of the wave travelling along the line divided by the speed of light in a vacuum, always a number less than 1. It is not light speed multiplied by anything, nor a shielding or impedance ratio. It tells you how much slower a signal moves in the cable than in free space.",
"A-007-002-006": "The ratio of the actual signal velocity in a line to the speed of light in a vacuum is called the velocity factor. Characteristic (surge) impedance describes the line's Z0, and SWR describes standing waves — neither is a velocity ratio. Velocity factor is what makes a cable's physical length shorter than its electrical length.",
"A-007-002-007": "Coaxial cable with a solid polyethylene dielectric typically has a velocity factor of about 0.66, meaning signals travel at about 66% of light speed inside it. A value of 2.7 is impossible (it would exceed light speed), and 0.33 or 0.1 are far too low for common coax. Remember 0.66 as the standard figure for solid-PE coax.",
"A-007-002-008": "The velocity factor is set by the dielectric (insulating) material between the conductors, because VF ≈ 1/√(dielectric constant). Line length, centre-conductor resistivity, and terminating impedance do not change how fast the wave propagates. Change the dielectric and you change the velocity factor.",
"A-007-002-009": "RF energy travels slower than the speed of light inside coax because of the dielectric, so a given electrical length (in wavelengths) corresponds to a shorter physical length. That is exactly what the velocity factor measures. Skin effect and parallel-line impedance are unrelated to why physical length is shorter than electrical length.",
"A-007-002-010": "Velocity factor equals 1/√(dielectric constant) — the reciprocal of the square root of the dielectric constant of the insulation between the conductors. VSWR, impedance, and losses are not given by this formula. So a higher dielectric constant lowers the velocity factor.",
"A-007-002-011": "Velocity factor is the ratio of the propagation velocity in the transmission line to the propagation velocity in free space, always less than 1. It is not the line's impedance, nor the free-space speed itself, nor anything about standing-wave reflection. It quantifies how much the line slows the wave compared with free space.",
"A-007-003-001": "Feeding the driven element in two places, symmetrically spaced a fraction of a wavelength on each side of centre, is the T match — its balanced, two-sided connection steps the antenna's low impedance up to the line. The gamma match is the unbalanced (one-sided) version of this idea, and a stub match uses a shorted line section instead. The two symmetric tap points are the giveaway for a T match.",
"A-007-003-002": "Feeding the driven element at the centre and at one point off to a single side is the unbalanced gamma match — \"unbalanced\" and \"one side\" point to gamma. The T match is the balanced two-sided version, and the stub match uses a separate line section. The single off-centre tap with a series capacitor is the hallmark of the gamma match.",
"A-007-003-003": "Connecting a short section of transmission line (a stub) near the antenna, perpendicular to the feedline, is the stub match; its length and position are tuned to cancel reactance and match impedance. Gamma and delta matches connect directly to the driven element instead. The separate shorted/open line section is what defines a stub match.",
"A-007-003-004": "Physical length = (free-space quarter wavelength) × velocity factor, where free-space λ/4 = 75 / f(MHz) metres. At 14.1 MHz, λ/4 = 75 / 14.1 = 5.32 m, then × 0.66 = 3.51 m (11.5 ft). The velocity factor shortens the cable, so always multiply the free-space length by VF.",
"A-007-003-005": "An unbalanced feed where the coax braid goes to the element centre and the centre conductor connects through a series variable capacitor to an adjustable rod on one side of the element is the gamma match. \"Lambda,\" \"zeta,\" and \"T\" do not describe this single-sided arrangement (the T match is two-sided and balanced). The series capacitor plus one-sided rod identifies it as gamma.",
"A-007-003-006": "Physical length = (free-space quarter wavelength) × velocity factor, with free-space λ/4 = 75 / f(MHz) metres. At 15 MHz, λ/4 = 75 / 15 = 5 m, then × 0.8 = 4 m (13.1 ft). The 0.8 velocity factor shrinks the 5 m free-space length to 4 m.",
"A-007-003-007": "Matching a driven element with a single adjustable rod and a series capacitor (one mechanical and one capacitive element on one side) describes the gamma match. The T match uses two symmetric rods, the omega match adds a second capacitor, and a \"Y\" match is not a standard term. One rod plus one capacitor equals gamma.",
"A-007-003-008": "In a gamma match the coaxial braid (shield) connects to the centre of the driven element, which is the electrical low-impedance point. The centre conductor goes through the series capacitor to the gamma rod instead. So braid-to-element-centre is the correct connection.",
"A-007-003-009": "The centre of the driven element in a gamma match connects to the coaxial braid (shield), grounding the element centre. The coax centre conductor connects through the variable capacitor to the gamma rod, not directly to the element centre. Element centre to braid is the rule.",
"A-007-003-010": "The adjustable gamma rod connects to the variable (series) capacitor, which in turn ties to the coax centre conductor; sliding the rod tap and tuning the capacitor sets the match. The rod does not connect to the reflector or directly to the element centre. Rod-to-capacitor is the correct link.",
"A-007-003-011": "In a gamma match the variable capacitor connects to the adjustable gamma rod (and on its other end to the coax centre conductor), forming the series-capacitor/rod tuning path. It does not connect to a director, the element centre, or the braid. Capacitor-to-rod completes the matching network.",
"A-007-004-001": "On a half-wave dipole the standing-wave pattern puts the voltage maximum at each open end, because the open ends cannot carry current and the wave reflects there as a voltage antinode. Current, not voltage, is what is lowest at the ends. High voltage at the tips is why dipole ends can arc at high power.",
"A-007-004-002": "Current is lowest (a node, near zero) at the open ends of a half-wave dipole, since current cannot flow past the open tips. Voltage is the quantity that is highest there. The current node at each end pairs with a voltage antinode.",
"A-007-004-003": "A centre-fed half-wave antenna is fed at the current maximum, which occurs at the centre, giving a convenient low feed-point impedance (~73 Ω). It is not a minimum-current or maximum-voltage point — those are at the ends. Feeding at the current maximum is why centre feeding is standard.",
"A-007-004-004": "Voltage is lowest at the middle of a half-wave dipole, where the standing-wave pattern has a voltage node and a current antinode. Current is at its maximum there, not its minimum. Low voltage plus high current at the centre gives the low feed-point impedance.",
"A-007-004-005": "Current is highest at the middle of a half-wave dipole, a current antinode, while voltage is at a node there. This high-current, low-voltage centre is exactly why the antenna is fed at the middle. The ends, by contrast, have high voltage and low current.",
"A-007-004-006": "A half-wave dipole is normally fed at its centre, the point of maximum current and minimum voltage, which gives a low and convenient feed impedance (~73 Ω). It is not fed where voltage or resistance is maximum. \"The antenna is resonant\" is true overall but does not identify the feed point — maximum current does.",
"A-007-004-007": "At the open ends of a half-wave dipole the voltage is high (antinode) and the current is low (node), the opposite of the centre. Both-high or both-low answers contradict the standing-wave pattern. High voltage at the tips is why end insulators and clearance matter.",
"A-007-004-008": "Impedance equals voltage divided by current, so the centre of a half-wave antenna has low impedance because voltage is low and current is high there. Both-high or both-low conditions would not give the characteristic ~73 Ω centre value. Low V over high I equals low Z.",
"A-007-004-009": "Minimum voltage on a half-wave dipole occurs at the centre, where the standing-wave pattern has a voltage node. The ends have maximum voltage, not minimum. The centre voltage minimum coincides with the current maximum.",
"A-007-004-010": "Minimum current on a half-wave dipole occurs at both ends, where the open tips force current nodes. The centre has maximum current, not minimum. Current minima at the ends pair with voltage maxima.",
"A-007-004-011": "Minimum impedance occurs at the centre of a half-wave dipole because impedance is voltage divided by current, and the centre has low voltage with high current. The ends, with high voltage and low current, have very high impedance. So minimum Z is at the centre.",
"A-007-005-001": "Circularly polarized waves are those whose electric field vector rotates steadily as the wave travels, tracing a helix rather than staying in one plane. It is not the field physically bent into a circle, nor waves circling the earth, nor simply any loop-antenna output. The defining feature is the continuously rotating electric field.",
"A-007-005-002": "Two crossed dipoles fed 90 degrees out of phase produce circular polarization, because the two perpendicular fields combine with a quarter-cycle time offset to make the resultant field rotate. They do not cancel; the phase offset is exactly what creates rotation. This is a common way to build a circularly polarized antenna for satellite work.",
"A-007-005-003": "A loaded helical-wound antenna is a physically short, inductively loaded vertical (a \"rubber duck\" style) and radiates linear polarization, so it does NOT produce circular polarization. Crossed dipoles fed 90 degrees apart, the Lindenblad, and the axial-mode helical all do produce circular polarization. Do not confuse the small loaded helix with the large axial-mode helical beam.",
"A-007-005-004": "Doppler shift matters most for contacts via satellite, because the satellite moves rapidly relative to the ground station, shifting the received frequency noticeably at VHF/UHF. Hilltop repeaters, handheld simplex, and slow terrestrial mobiles produce negligible Doppler. The high relative velocity of a satellite is the cause.",
"A-007-005-005": "Crossing two linearly polarized antennas at 90 degrees causes a large polarization mismatch, giving a theoretical loss of 20 dB or more over a fixed path. The smaller 3, 6, or 10 dB figures understate it; in theory the loss approaches infinity but practically 20+ dB is observed. Full cross-polarization is a severe mismatch.",
"A-007-005-006": "Newtonian is a reflecting-telescope configuration, not a parabolic-dish feed arrangement, so it is NOT a valid dish illumination method. Front feed, offset feed, and Cassegrain are all real ways to illuminate a parabolic reflector. The trap is borrowing the optical telescope term where it does not apply to RF dish feeds.",
"A-007-005-007": "A parabola is efficient because its geometry focuses all the parallel incoming energy onto a single focal point where the pickup (feed) antenna sits, concentrating the captured signal. It is not about needing no matching or using a particular dipole or horn shape. The focusing of energy to the focal point is the key.",
"A-007-005-008": "A right-hand circularly polarized helical-beam antenna best receives right-hand polarized signals; matching the sense of rotation gives maximum response. A left-hand signal would be strongly rejected (large mismatch loss). Polarization sense must match for circular antennas.",
"A-007-005-009": "A quad antenna responds to both vertical and horizontal polarization because its loop has conductor segments oriented in both directions, picking up either field component. A helical beam is circularly polarized, a folded dipole is linear, and a ground plane is vertical. The loop geometry of the quad gives the dual-polarization response.",
"A-007-005-010": "For amateur parabolic reflectors the surface accuracy should be kept within about 0.1 wavelength (lambda) to avoid scattering and gain loss; errors are measured relative to wavelength, not as a fixed millimetre figure or a percentage of diameter. The 0.25 lambda figure is too loose. Tying the tolerance to wavelength is the correct approach.",
"A-007-005-011": "A parabolic dish's gain depends on its diameter measured in wavelengths — the larger the aperture relative to wavelength, the higher the gain. Feed polarization, focal length, and dish material do not set the gain (focal length affects feed placement, not gain). Gain scales with (diameter / wavelength) squared.",
"A-007-006-001": "Work in decibels: net gain = antenna gain minus losses = 6 dBd − 3 dB = +3 dB. Since +3 dB means doubling power, ERP = 100 W × 2 = 200 watts. Convert dB to a power ratio (3 dB = ×2) and apply it to the transmitter output.",
"A-007-006-002": "Higher SWR means standing waves of higher current and voltage exist along the line, and the increased current and voltage drive greater I²R conductor heating and dielectric heating losses. The added loss is heat dissipated in the cable, not radiation or leakage to ground. So the cause is dielectric and conductor heat losses.",
"A-007-006-003": "First subtract the line loss in watts: 200 W − 5 W = 195 W reaching the antenna. The antenna gain of 3 dBd doubles power (3 dB = ×2), so ERP = 195 × 2 = 390 watts. Here the loss is given in watts, so subtract it directly before applying the gain.",
"A-007-006-004": "Effective Radiated Power is the transmitter output power minus the feedline (and connector) losses, plus the antenna gain expressed relative to a dipole (dBd). It is not pre-modulation power, raw line power, or a simple input/output ratio. ERP = power delivered to the antenna times the antenna's gain over a dipole.",
"A-007-006-005": "Combine in decibels: net = 9 dBd − 3 dB = +6 dB. Each 3 dB doubles power, so +6 dB is ×4; ERP = 200 W × 4 = 800 watts. Add gains and subtract losses in dB first, then convert the net dB to a power ratio.",
"A-007-006-006": "Add up the decibels: −1.30 − 0.2 + 4.50 = +3.0 dB net. A net of +3 dB doubles the power, so ERP = 100 W × 2 = 200 watts. Sum all losses and gains in dB before converting to a power multiplier.",
"A-007-006-007": "Increasing overall station gain by 3 dB doubles the effective radiated power, because +3 dB always corresponds to a power ratio of 2. ERP does not stay the same or fall — it rises. Remember the rule: every 3 dB doubles power.",
"A-007-006-008": "Sum the decibels: −0.8 − 0.2 + 10 = +9.0 dB net. A power ratio of +9 dB is about ×7.94 (9 dB = three 3-dB doublings, 2×2×2 = 8), so ERP ≈ 125 W × 7.94 ≈ 992 W ≈ 1000 watts. Combine all dB first, then apply the ratio to the output power.",
"A-007-006-009": "Replacing a 3 dBd antenna with a 9 dBd antenna is a net gain change of +6 dB. Since +6 dB is two doublings (×2 then ×2 = ×4), the ERP increases by a factor of 4. Convert the dB difference, not the dB numbers themselves, into the power ratio.",
"A-007-006-010": "Net change = 10 dBd − 1 dB = +9 dB, which is a power ratio of about ×7.94 (≈ 8). ERP ≈ 2000 W × 7.94 ≈ 15 880 W ≈ 16 000 watts PEP. Add gains and subtract losses in dB, then convert the +9 dB to roughly an eightfold increase.",
"A-007-006-011": "Net change = 10 dBd − 1 dB = +9 dB, a power ratio of about ×7.94 (≈ 8). ERP ≈ 1000 W × 7.94 ≈ 7940 W ≈ 8000 watts PEP. As with the 2000 W case, +9 dB means roughly eight times the power.",
"A-007-007-001": "For a horizontal Yagi over flat ground, raising the antenna lowers the main-lobe takeoff angle, because ground reflection interference moves the first lobe nearer the horizon as height increases. So the takeoff angle decreases with increasing height. Lower takeoff angles favour long-distance (DX) propagation.",
"A-007-007-002": "A simple horizontal antenna needs to be about a half wavelength or more above ground before ground reflections shape it into a directional pattern; below that it tends toward a high-angle, nearly omnidirectional cloud-warmer. Heights of an eighth, quarter, or three-eighths wavelength are too low for significant directivity. Half a wavelength is the practical threshold.",
"A-007-007-003": "The effective ground plane — the level from which reflections appear to occur — is not the visible surface but lies several centimetres up to about 2 metres below ground, depending on soil conductivity. Poorer soil pushes the reflection plane deeper. It is not at exact ground level or above ground.",
"A-007-007-004": "A ground-mounted quarter-wave vertical radiates at a lower vertical angle than a dipole only a quarter wavelength high, and the lower takeoff angle is what aids long-distance contacts. Lower radiation resistance, omnidirectionality, and vertical polarization are real traits but are not the reason for better DX. The low radiation angle is the key advantage.",
"A-007-007-005": "At exactly one-half wavelength high, ground reflection from a horizontal dipole interferes such that straight-up (vertical) radiation is effectively cancelled, concentrating energy at lower angles. The pattern is altered, not unaffected, but it does not simply produce lobes at 15 and 50 degrees or cancel side lobes. The notable effect is suppression of the overhead component.",
"A-007-007-006": "Antenna height changes the elevation pattern, but for the horizontal (azimuthal) pattern, when a horizontal dipole is less than half a wavelength high, ground reflections significantly distort it. At greater heights the azimuthal pattern stabilizes near the free-space figure-eight. Low height plus strong ground reflection equals a distorted horizontal pattern.",
"A-007-007-007": "For long-distance (DX) propagation the vertical radiation (takeoff) angle should be low, less than 30 degrees, so signals leave near the horizon and travel far per ionospheric hop. High angles (45–90 degrees) send energy nearly straight up, good only for short range or NVIS. Lower angle means longer reach.",
"A-007-007-008": "Decreasing the antenna's vertical radiation angle lets each ionospheric hop cover more ground, so multiple-hop paths span greater total distance. Power, antenna height (directly), and element length are not what extends multi-hop range — the takeoff angle is. A lower angle stretches each hop.",
"A-007-007-009": "A dipole mounted very high (more than about 3 wavelengths up) approaches its free-space centre impedance of roughly 73 Ω, nearest the 75 Ω choice. Near ground the impedance varies widely, but at great height ground effects fade out. So 75 Ω is the expected value.",
"A-007-007-010": "A horizontal antenna mounted low radiates mostly at high angles, and the ground acts as a reflector to send energy nearly straight up and back down nearby — ideal for short-range (NVIS-style) contacts on lower HF bands. It is not about noise temperature, low angle, or higher radiation resistance. The low height plus ground reflection gives high-angle coverage for close-in work.",
"A-007-007-011": "NVIS works by firing nearly straight up so signals reflect back down over a wide local area, which calls for a horizontal antenna less than 1/4 wavelength above ground and a frequency below the current critical frequency (so the ionosphere still reflects the high-angle signal). A half-wave-high antenna radiates too low for NVIS, and verticals radiate at low angles. Low antenna plus below-critical frequency is the recipe.",
"A-007-008-001": "Radiation resistance is the equivalent resistance that would dissipate the same power that the antenna actually radiates into space — a useful fiction for accounting for radiated power as if it were resistive loss. It is not an atmospheric resistance, the antenna's specific impedance, or combined ohmic/line losses. It represents radiated power as an equivalent resistance.",
"A-007-008-002": "Knowing the radiation resistance lets you match the feedline and transmitter to the antenna for maximum power transfer, since it is the resistive part of the feed-point impedance. It is not used to measure near-field density or compute front-to-side or front-to-back ratios. Impedance matching is the practical reason.",
"A-007-008-003": "Radiation resistance depends on the antenna's surroundings (nearby objects, height over ground) and on the conductor's length-to-diameter ratio, which together set how effectively it radiates. It is not fixed for all antennas, nor set by feedline length or sunspots. Geometry and environment determine it.",
"A-007-008-004": "The ratio of radiation resistance to total resistance is the antenna efficiency, since it tells what fraction of input power is radiated rather than lost as heat. Beamwidth, ERP, and radiation conversion loss are different quantities. Efficiency = radiated portion / total.",
"A-007-008-005": "Total antenna-system resistance is the radiation resistance plus the ohmic (loss) resistance of conductors, ground, and connections. It does not include transmission-line resistance or any \"space impedance\" term in this definition. Radiation resistance accounts for useful power, ohmic resistance for wasted heat.",
"A-007-008-006": "Beamwidth is found by locating the two angles on either side of the main lobe where the signal has dropped 3 dB (to half power) from the peak, then taking the angular difference between them. It is not measured from element geometry or from front-to-side/front-to-back ratios. The 3 dB (half-power) points define beamwidth.",
"A-007-008-007": "Percent efficiency = (radiation resistance / total resistance) × 100, the fraction of power radiated rather than lost, expressed as a percent. Dividing total by radiation resistance, or using transmission resistance, gives the wrong formula. Radiation over total, times 100.",
"A-007-008-008": "Radiation resistance is the equivalent resistance that would dissipate the same energy the antenna radiates into space. The j factor and K factor are unrelated, and \"antenna resistance\" is a vaguer term that can include losses. The specific definition of equal-energy-equivalent resistance is radiation resistance.",
"A-007-008-009": "Antenna beamwidth is the angular distance between the two half-power points (where power is down 3 dB) on the major lobe. It is measured on the main lobe, not on a minor lobe, and uses the 3 dB (half-power), not 6 dB, points. Half-power points on the major lobe define beamwidth.",
"A-007-008-010": "Efficiency = radiation resistance / total resistance × 100, where total = radiation + ohmic = 72 + 2 = 74 Ω. So efficiency = 72 / 74 × 100 = 97.3%. The small 2 Ω of loss against 72 Ω of radiation gives a very efficient antenna.",
"A-007-008-011": "Efficiency = radiation resistance / (radiation + ohmic) × 100 = 50 / (50 + 2) × 100 = 50 / 52 × 100 = 96.15%. Both resistances are in milliohms, but the units cancel in the ratio so you can use the numbers directly. Even tiny loss against the radiation resistance keeps efficiency high.",
"A-007-009-001": "Waveguide is practical only at very high (microwave) frequencies, typically above 3000 MHz, because its physical size must be comparable to the wavelength — at low frequencies it would be impossibly large. The below-150 MHz and below-1500 MHz options are wrong for this reason. Above 3000 MHz the wavelength is small enough for reasonable waveguide dimensions.",
"A-007-009-002": "Waveguide is efficient because it has low radiation, dielectric (it is air-filled), and copper losses — but \"low hysteresis loss\" is not a meaningful reason, since hysteresis applies to magnetic materials, not a hollow conductor. The question asks which is NOT correct, so the hysteresis answer is the odd one out. Waveguide's low loss comes from its air dielectric and large conductive surfaces.",
"A-007-009-003": "The major advantage of waveguide is its very low loss at microwave frequencies compared with coax. Being expensive, heavy, and hard to install are disadvantages, and \"frequency sensitive based on dimensions\" describes a limitation, not an advantage. Low loss is the benefit.",
"A-007-009-004": "A rectangular waveguide will not propagate energy unless its wide dimension is at least one-half wavelength, which sets its cutoff frequency. Smaller than half a wavelength and the wave is cut off and cannot pass. The half-wavelength minimum is the key dimensional rule.",
"A-007-009-005": "Waveguide behaves like a high-pass filter: it has low loss above its cutoff frequency and very high loss (no propagation) below cutoff — so the statement claiming the opposite (low loss below cutoff) is NOT correct. The TE and TM mode descriptions are accurate. Remember: waveguide passes frequencies above cutoff, blocks those below.",
"A-007-009-006": "Waveguide's major advantage over coax at microwave frequencies is its very low loss. The 1.8 MHz–24 GHz range is wrong (waveguide cannot work at HF), and waveguide is neither easy nor cheap to install. Low loss is the standout benefit at microwaves.",
"A-007-009-007": "A transmission line formed as a conductor trace over a ground plane on a printed circuit board is called microstripline (microstrip). \"Dielectric substrate\" and \"ground plane\" are parts of it, not the line's name, and \"dielectric imprinting\" is not a term. Microstripline is the PCB transmission line.",
"A-007-009-008": "Because microstrip's conductor is exposed on the board surface (only the ground plane is beneath it), it has poorer shielding than coaxial cable, which fully surrounds the centre conductor. It need not have especially low or high characteristic impedance. The open structure means more radiation and pickup than coax.",
"A-007-009-009": "A section of waveguide acts like a high-pass filter: signals above the cutoff frequency pass with low loss while those below cutoff are blocked. It does not behave like a low-pass or band-stop filter. The cutoff behaviour gives it its high-pass character.",
"A-007-009-010": "Stripline is a printed-circuit transmission line, with a conductor sandwiched between two ground planes inside the board dielectric. It is not a semiconductor family, an antenna, or a cleaning fluid. Like microstrip, it is a PCB transmission-line technique used at high frequencies.",
"A-007-009-011": "Before working on a microwave feed horn or waveguide, make sure the transmitter is off and its power source is disconnected, because microwave RF energy can cause serious internal heating and burns to body tissue. Weather, propagation conditions, and clothing are not the safety priority here. Removing the RF hazard by powering down and disconnecting is the essential precaution."
};
